commit_message:
Accessing the shell

Public key for target nodes defined in Settings tab; doc'ed
in User Guide section.

New section in Operations Guide covers:
- 0100-public-keys -- how to manually upload a Public Key
- 0200-ssh-fuel-master -- how to ssh into Fuel Master
- 0300-ssh-target-nodes -- how to ssh into target nodes

The XFS and two Galera sections were erroneously nested
under "Introduction" so I had to make those top-level headers
to avoid having them nested under this material.

Change-Id: Idc457ac705be5a1e505e3721efbddd331d4bd973
Closes-Bug: 1375825

Thank you for your first contribution to OpenStack.

    Your patch will now be tested automatically by OpenStack testing frameworks
    and once the automatic tests pass, it will be reviewed by other friendly
    developers. They will give you feedback and may require you to refine it.

    People seldom get their patch approved on the first try, so don't be
    concerned if requested to make corrections. Feel free to modify your patch
    and resubmit a new change-set.

    Patches usually take 3 to 7 days to be reviewed so be patient and be
    available on IRC to ask and answer questions about your work. The more you
    participate in the community the more rewarding it is for you. You may also
    notice that the more you get to know people and get to be known, the faster
    your patches will be reviewed and eventually approved. Get to know others

commit_message:
Increase timeout of waiting the service in check_ceph_status()

Two minutes is not enough for starting ceph service during our
destructive tests, especially in case of some failures.

Change-Id: I892cf7596584ef829475fd6583e869a5109bc1d6
Related-Bug: #1318638

commit_message:
Add voluptuous for libraries/applications data validation

The voluptuous library *can* be nicer to interact with and
is slightly more powerful (and pythonic) than the json-schema
library for data-validation.

It would be great to have it available for applications and
libraries in openstack to use for there validation of data
or other inputs/outputs (if they so choose to use it over
json-schema).

The current version in ubuntu trusty is 0.8.2, while fedora
seems to have access to 0.8.5 (so thats why the lower bound
is being set at 0.8.2 in this change).

Change-Id: Ie61e25e968c1a562c9a314a5862220e1919db11b

commit_message:
Big Switch: Fix SSL version on get_server_cert

The ssl.get_server_certificate method uses SSLv3 by default.
Support for SSLv3 was dropped on the backend controller in
response to the POODLE vulnerability. This patch fixes it
to use TLSv1 like the wrap_socket method.

Closes-Bug: #1384487
Change-Id: I9cb5f219d327d62168bef2d7dbee22534b2e454e
(cherry picked from commit 77e283c94f51e21dcf126a316098c54a7cdfca0f)

commit_message:
Big Switch: Fix SSL version on get_server_cert

The ssl.get_server_certificate method uses SSLv3 by default.
Support for SSLv3 was dropped on the backend controller in
response to the POODLE vulnerability. This patch fixes it
to use TLSv1 like the wrap_socket method.

Closes-Bug: #1384487
Change-Id: I9cb5f219d327d62168bef2d7dbee22534b2e454e
(cherry picked from commit 77e283c94f51e21dcf126a316098c54a7cdfca0f)

Funcionally testing I'm getting a (seemingly spurious) warning message when using --no-ssl-compression.

 $ glance  --os-image-url https://0.0.0.0:9292 --os-auth-token $TOKEN  image-show 4b5d343e-d2d5-43f0-92b8-5404bb8ec112Error finding address for https://0.0.0.0:9292/v1/images/4b5d343e-d2d5-43f0-92b8-5404bb8ec112: [Errno 1] _ssl.c:504: error:14090086:SSL routines:SSL3_GET_SERVER_CERTIFICATE:certificate verify failed

correctly fails.


with --no-ssl-compression (and no ca cert specified):

$ glance --no-ssl-compression  --os-image-url https://0.0.0.0:9292 --os-auth-token $TOKEN  image-show 4b5d343e-d2d5-43f0-92b8-5404bb8ec112

  InsecureRequestWarning)

without --no-ssl-compression, with os-cacert:

commit_message:
Don't replace the https handler in the poolmanager

In order to keep the support for `--ssl-nocompression` it was decided to
overwrite the https HTTPAdapter in `requests` poolmanager. Although this
seemed to work correctly, it was causing some issues when using
glanceclient from other services that rely on requests and that were
also configured to use TLS.

THis patch changes implements a different strategy by using
`glance+https` as the scheme to use when `no-compression` is requested.

Closes-bug: #1350251
Closes-bug: #1347150
Closes-bug: #1362766

Change-Id: Ib25237ba821ee20a561a163b79402d1375ebed0b

commit_message:
Pylint Fixes (bad-builtin, bad-indentation, duplicate-key)

Removes the following pylint exceptions and fixes the violations:
 * bad-builtin
 * bad-indentation
 * duplicate-key

This change prefers using all() and any() over allowing indentation
of complex multi-line if statements to match up against the block
that the if statement creates. This was previously solved by
double-indenting in several places.

Change-Id: I1d5a2c2eedf10be5f4cf3fda179a0e872efe8c12

commit_message:
Spread the metrics better across kafka partitions

The previous code used the metric timestamp as the key for routing across
the kafka partitions. Since the timestamp is only accurate to the
second and we are expection > 20k metrics per second, this did not use
the kafka partitions well. The new code uses the timestamp plus
the count of metrics seen so far as the key. Performance tests
show a much better distribution

The meter metrics.published was changed to really count all metrics
instead of batches as it did previously

A new meter batches.published was created that counts the batches.

Change-Id: If2c58a19b2ae0056134385617a11877bb7f936e6

commit_message:
List uploaded stage logs for an assembly

This commit adds a proper resource for Userlogs,
and exposes the list via the API. Previously the
relationship was being recorded in the userlogs table

os-refresh-config/post-configure.d/51-rabbitmq

needs a careful read-through; note that the cluster_size doesn't fail if the BOOTSTRAP_NODE isn't running rabbit - it returns 0 (which matches the first half of the while condition).

The point of this is to take a problem that's theoretically impossible to solve (coordination of distributed processes in the absence of a message-passing system) and turn it into one that we _can_ tackle (by adding a clock).

There's a good, explicit failure case too: if the clustering fails, we're going to need human intervention."}, {'account_id': 10373, 'date': '2014-09-25 12:32:29.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 28.'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2014-09-25 12:32:34.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 28: Verified+1

Cloese-Bug: 1334314
'}, {'created': '2014-08-20 07:49:15.000000000', 'message': 'Add normal exit to rabbitmq upstart config

Change-Id: Ic758256481fdd31d10f4e4a341ae93cb372a0766
Closes-Bug: #1334314
'}, {'created': '2014-09-16 10:24:43.000000000', 'message': 'Fix RabbitMQ element clustering start and stop

Prevent upstart respawning from SIGTERM due to post-stop pkill running.

Separate config files out of the install.d script into files to help
readability.

Graceful start and stop, to prevent split-brain issues. In the non-cluster
case: just restart.

In the cluster case: stop everything gracefully. Start everything. Join
bootstrap node if not bootstrap, otherwise join any node. This prevents getting
two disjoint clusters.

"graceful" means RAM nodes sync with disk nodes before they stop. If they are
stopped unceremoniously, they lose data.

Closes-Bug: #1334314
Change-Id: Ic758256481fdd31d10f4e4a341ae93cb372a0766

'}, {'created': '2014-09-18 18:29:23.000000000', 'message': 'Fix RabbitMQ element clustering start and stop

Prevent upstart respawning from SIGTERM due to post-stop pkill running.

Separate config files out of the install.d script into files to help
readability.

Graceful start and stop, to prevent split-brain issues. In the non-cluster
case: just restart.

In the cluster case: stop everything gracefully. Start everything. Join
bootstrap node if not bootstrap, otherwise join any node. This prevents getting
two disjoint clusters.

"graceful" means RAM nodes sync with disk nodes before they stop. If they are
stopped unceremoniously, they lose data.

Closes-Bug: #1334314
Change-Id: Ic758256481fdd31d10f4e4a341ae93cb372a0766

commit_message:
Fix RabbitMQ element clustering start and stop

Prevent upstart respawning from SIGTERM due to post-stop pkill running.

Separate config files out of the install.d script into files to help
readability.

Renumber 40-rabbitmq to 51-rabbitmq and 50-rabbitmq-passwords to
52-rabbitmq-passwords so that ntp runs before these scripts

Graceful start and stop, to prevent split-brain issues. In the non-cluster
case: just restart.

In the cluster case: stop everything gracefully. Start everything. Join
bootstrap node if not bootstrap, otherwise join any node. This prevents getting
two disjoint clusters.

"graceful" means RAM nodes sync with disk nodes before they stop. If they are
stopped unceremoniously, they lose data.

Closes-Bug: #1334314
Change-Id: Ic758256481fdd31d10f4e4a341ae93cb372a0766

commit_message:
L3 Agent: allow to automatically reschedule virtual routers

In case of L3 agent failure, allow to reschedule automatically a virtual
router.

It's another way to provide HA for virtual routers with medium downtime.
The best way stays in using keepalived + DVR features but this
parameters allows another way to provide HA.

Change-Id: I0527e4a368e2b90b83877d3c7861e86674f9ae8a

commit_message:
Rename _handle_saml2_tokens() method

Since federation is going to support other protocols than saml2,
renaming the _handle_saml2_tokens() method to _handle_federation_tokens()

Change-Id: I9682c41c3982838dcb280c4a093d1123bc740090
Closes-Bug: 1389583

commit_message:
Rename "thing" to "resource"

Some scenario method use the ambiguous name "thing" while actually referring
openstack resources.

Change-Id: Ia0697a37871ee04c4bd7eec00fad19065b936da0

commit_message:
Ask for password during upgrade

Upgrades will no longer use password stored in astute.yaml
Now there are two ways to pass admin password to upgrade script:
* new `--password` argument in CLI
* prompt for password when password was not specified by `--password`
When no password was provided error is raised.

Changed where logging is initialized to make CLI tests easier

DocImpact
Implements: blueprint access-control-master-node-improvments

Change-Id: Icc0f952729517fb94ee90ab98b0ee313bc213330

[{'created': '2014-10-29 10:39:29.000000000', 'message': "Update admin guide on handling drive failures

Simply replacing a failed disk requires a very long time if the ring is not
changed, because all data will be replicated to a single new disk. This extends
the time to recover from missing replicas, and becomes even more important with
bigger disks.

This patch updates the doc to include a faster alternative by setting the weight
of a failed disk to 0.  In this case the partitions from the failed disk are
distributed and replicated to the remaining disks in the cluster, and because
each disk gets only a fraction of the partitions it's also much faster.

Change-Id: I16617756359771ad89ca5d4690b58a014f481d9b
"}]
commit_message:
Update admin guide on handling drive failures

Simply replacing a failed disk requires a very long time if the ring is not
changed, because all data will be replicated to a single new disk. This extends
the time to recover from missing replicas, and becomes even more important with
bigger disks.

This patch updates the doc to include a faster alternative by setting the weight
of a failed disk to 0.  In this case the partitions from the failed disk are
distributed and replicated to the remaining disks in the cluster, and because
each disk gets only a fraction of the partitions it's also much faster.

Change-Id: I16617756359771ad89ca5d4690b58a014f481d9b

commit_message:
Unscoped federated user-specific commands

A federated user can authenticate with the v3unscopedsaml plugin and
list the domains and projects she is allowed to scope to.
This patch introduces the new commands 'federation domain list' and
'federation project list'.
Note that for these commands -and plugin- to be available, the lxml
library must be installed.

Change-Id: I2707b624befcfb0a01b40a094e12fd68a3ee7773
Co-Authored-By: Florent Flament <florent.flament-ext@cloudwatt.com>

Tests with linear growing of number of nodes in the environment.

Tests are not passed, due to low speed of some operations.
This set of tests should be used as part of acceptance tests for fuel-1k blueprint.

Change-Id: Ic747e8e9781393a0cc076e1e3f6f3d35db1c4f65
Blueprint: fuel-1k

Since these are being changed we should make them consistent with the recommendation for how to specify log messages.

If the message is only used in a log it is recommended to put the message in the log call and it is recommended to pass the replacement text as a parameter to logging instead of doing the formatting.   So they should look like: 

LOG.error(_LE('...'), {...})

Note that if a message is passed outside of the context, such as used to create an exception, the message should be formatted using _() because it could be used as part of a user facing message.

A lot of the message follow this, I tried to flag the ones you are changing that didn't."}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2014-10-13 05:06:59.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 5: Verified+1

commit_message:
Make servicegroup use fit for i18n log rule

Currently files under nova/servicegroup, nova/volume,
nova/keymgr and nova/image  folder didn't fit for i18n log rule,
this patch updates it.

[{'created': '2014-11-05 11:09:39.000000000', 'message': 'Remove test_barbican from keymgr tests

Unfortunately it seems we have some very poorly
written keymgr unit tests, specifically
keymgr/test_barbican.py does this:
from barbicanclient.common import auth

First problem is that from a unit test perspective
that pretty much sucks, second problem is that
barbicanclient as of version 3.0.0.0 no longer
has an "auth" module, as a result Cinderunit tests
now fail.

The test_barbican.py unit tests need to be rewritten
to mock out the client components and actually test
Cinder components where needed without relying on
the barbicanclient.

For now in order to free up the gate, remove test_barbican.py

Change-Id: Id770c87c0d622ae4c1e0d71141ffa9aed29be2ec
Partial-Bug: #1389419
(cherry picked from commit 37e4a12652c803d60c18079b735d96e5c7890f07)
'}]
commit_message:
Remove test_barbican from keymgr tests

Unfortunately it seems we have some very poorly
written keymgr unit tests, specifically
keymgr/test_barbican.py does this:
from barbicanclient.common import auth

First problem is that from a unit test perspective
that pretty much sucks, second problem is that
barbicanclient as of version 3.0.0.0 no longer
has an "auth" module, as a result Cinderunit tests
now fail.

The test_barbican.py unit tests need to be rewritten
to mock out the client components and actually test
Cinder components where needed without relying on
the barbicanclient.

For now in order to free up the gate, remove test_barbican.py

Change-Id: Id770c87c0d622ae4c1e0d71141ffa9aed29be2ec
Partial-Bug: #1389419
(cherry picked from commit 37e4a12652c803d60c18079b735d96e5c7890f07)

commit_message:
Remove some duplicate unit tests

There are several locations where some unit test mixins are
incorrectly used multiple times with an otherwise same configuration,
which results in pointless re-runs of the same unit test. Similarily,
there are a few tests defined in classes inherited by multiple tests
that don't change behavior in the child tests so they are run multiple
times as well.

This patch eliminates the duplicates and moves some test cases from
their parent class into a subclass when they don't need to be run multiple
times. The result is 221 fewer test runs (~1.5% of the tests run).

Closes-Bug: #1374836
Change-Id: I292091488cd944510fa1250920d41be2a50dabaf

commit_message:
Tuskar: support packaged heat templates

Updates the tusker 90-tuskar-db-sync so that it works
properly when using tripleo-heat-templates that
get installed via a package.

Change-Id: I4116e7e2651a29a7260c12d134cd856897fde2a2

cool, thanks for working on this :).

the package-installs-* files for the individual install types (package vs source) need to be named with the element name only.

so instead of:

  package-installs-heat-engine-package-install
  package-installs-heat-engine-source-install

it needs to be:

  package-installs-heat-engine

in both directories. This is b/c the package-installs scripts strip "package-installs-" off the front of the filename to get the element name  to use to send to pkg-map to map packages.

This is how I've done it in the package install type support for ceilometer for reference:

commit_message:
Return 403 on unauthorized upload when over account quota

If you try an unauthorized upload into a container that is over quota you get
a 403 instead of a 413, but if you try to unauthorized upload when an
*account* is over quota you can see the 413 even though the upload would have
been rejected by the authorize callback.  By wrapping the authorize callback
associated with the incoming request we can make sure to only return our 413
when the request would have been authorized otherwise.

Drive by doc fixes thanks to acoles:

 * State that container_quotas should be after auth middleware in
   the class doc string.
 * Add note to proxy-server.conf.sample that account_quotas should
   be after auth middleware.

The equivalent statements are already in place for each quota
middleware.

Doc-Impact

Closes-Bug: #1387415
Change-Id: I2a88b3ec79d35bfdd73ea6ad64e376b7c7af4ea6

commit_message:
Add CLI tests for actions

- Fix wrong inheritance in basa.py
- Added action_v2.yaml with simple action definition that describe
two actions
- Added positive tests which cover all CLI action commands
- Added negative tests

Change-Id: I075868aaff5f218718933c40bb99b4415ca80821

Tests for extension, db and plugin for LBaaS V2

Adding needed driver interface changes for tests.
Adding LoggingNoop driver needed changes for tests.
Adding extension, plugin, and db unit tests.

Partially-implements: blueprint lbaas-api-and-objmodel-improvement

commit_message:
Alarms listing based on "timestamp"

Co-Authored-By: Ilya Tyaptin <ityaptin@mirantis.com>

Fixes are proposed for ordering alarms based
on "timestamp" in descending order.
Existing tests has been modified at storage
and api without breaking their functionality.

One test case has been provided with this patch.

Change-Id: Ie2bb950b6d32188f451f905e2cf07e4d938df1ac
Closes-Bug: #1287119

Add ordering for returned alarms in impl_hbase

Added descending timestamp ordering for alarms are returned by
"get_alarms" in "impl_hbase" module. Used builtin "sorted"
function, because HBase doesn't have any possibilities for
custom ordering.

Change-Id: Ib05adc45ff8b9b419cf606641f4983fe8090b1e6
Related-bug: #1287119

commit_message:
Using of $(PRODUCT_VERSION) dependent upstream mirrors

This feature allows to freeze version of upstream mirrors
for each version of product separately.

Closes-Bug: #1377125
Change-Id: I2df5fe9c00aad06dd355c4ea0c956648f0ce2eaf

commit_message:
Fix KeystoneClient issue when token was expired

KeystoneClient should always first try to use username/password and only if
they are not provided, do a fallback to this.token. Otherwise for expired
tokens login is not possible.

Related-Bug: #1375622
(cherry picked from commit d8d9d96608f759d765ec0b1016e7363229ffc35a)

Change-Id: Ia85278402799d7d19e0c0aee975cc986de5879f9

commit_message:
Remove storing of password in browser

Plaintext password was stored in localStorage. This was removed and replaced
by token.
Username is still stored -- we display it in the navigation bar.
Tests were updated to use only the token and a check for username in navbar
was added.

Implements: blueprint access-control-master-node-improvments
(cherry picked from commit c1ee8dfede79b354601f389a91a7244a2920945a)

Conflicts:
	nailgun/static/js/app.js
	nailgun/static/js/views/dialogs.jsx
	nailgun/static/js/views/layout.jsx
	nailgun/static/js/views/login_page.jsx

Change-Id: Id9a053e119f6826eda5472629f7d09e618297403

i have a few concerns with this patch.

1. it removes the rootwrap logic that was in place, i think we might still want to use the rootwrap especially if the default proxy command uses namespaces.

2. if the intention is to remove the rootwrap, then there are a few more places it needs to be excised from. in the current state this patch leaves the config options and the documentation in place for rootwrap.

3. i think we will need to document this change in the advanced configurations documentation.

4. if we end up removing the rootwrap logic from within Sahara we might still want to leave the executable and give the user clear instruction on when they will want to include the rootwrap in their proxy_command.'}, {'account_id': 12561, 'date': '2014-10-27 16:41:33.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1: Workflow-1

Michael, thank you for your feedback.

through a proxy (both for SSH and HTTP connections). Currently Sahara
reaches them using a hard-coded proxy command. This patch makes this
command user-definable in the configuration file.

commit_message:
Make proxy command generic and user-definable

When using Sahara with use_floating_ips=false, instances are accessed
through a proxy (both for SSH and HTTP connections). Currently Sahara
reaches them using a hard-coded proxy command. This patch makes this
command user-definable in the configuration file.

Changes:
- Move HTTP adapters logic out of Neutron-related code.
- Transform the neutron proxy command into a generic one:
    'ip netns exec qrouter-{router_id} nc {host} {port}'
- Use user-defined proxy command when proxy_command is set in conf;
  the hard-coded proxy command when use_floating_ips=false and
  use_namespaces=true; otherwise no proxy.
- Add tests for those three possibilities + misconfiguration.

Examples of use:
- proxy_command='ip netns exec ns_for_{network_id} nc {host} {port}'
- proxy_command='ssh proxy-machine-{tenant_id} nc {host} {port}'

Change-Id: Iac033659e97b1ad935bb7be84de9fc731f787f4b
Closes-Bug: #1386193

commit_message:
Fix incorrect ca arguments for calling ceilometer client

With ceilometer configured with SSL, Horizon fail to connect to
ceilometer to load the meters(usage data) due to it passed a wrong
of ca argument for ceilometer client. Should use 'cacert' instead
of 'ca_file'.

See ceilometer client:
https://github.com/openstack/python-ceilometerclient/blob/master/ceilometerclient/v2/client.py#L53

Change-Id: I296c61119e07cd2e19079ef62054c5837fa13114
Closes-Bug: #1388764

commit_message:
Use internalURL for ceilometer-agent-compute

Compute nodes cannot reach public VIP w/o
br-ex mappings configured. In order to allow
ceilometer compute agent to communicate with
API endpoints, use internalURL.

Closes-bug: #1388745

Change-Id: Id32f551ffb79f8e32660cee7b167176c800ac54d
Signed-off-by: Bogdan Dobrelya <bdobrelia@mirantis.com>

commit_message:
Use internalURL for ceilometer-agent-compute

Compute nodes cannot reach public VIP w/o
br-ex mappings configured. In order to allow
ceilometer compute agent to communicate with
API endpoints, use internalURL.

Closes-bug: #1388745

Change-Id: Id32f551ffb79f8e32660cee7b167176c800ac54d
Signed-off-by: Bogdan Dobrelya <bdobrelia@mirantis.com>

commit_message:
Fixed cluster scaling in distributed mode

API has no way to get engine version without RPC call. Replaced
direct method call with RPC call.

Change-Id: I8b6db54c7eb4b58167c8266bc58f180ccd2bbe13

[{'created': '2014-11-04 22:38:43.000000000', 'message': 'Remove test_barbican from keymgr tests

Unfortunately it seems we have some very poorly
written keymgr unit tests, specifically
keymgr/test_barbican.py does this:
from barbicanclient.common import auth

First problem is that from a unit test perspective
that pretty much sucks, second problem is that
barbicanclient as of version 3.0.0.0 no longer
has an "auth" module, as a result Cinderunit tests
now fail.

The test_barbican.py unit tests need to be rewritten
to mock out the client components and actually test
Cinder components where needed without relying on
the barbicanclient.

For now in order to free up the gate, remove test_barbican.py

Change-Id: Id770c87c0d622ae4c1e0d71141ffa9aed29be2ec
Partial-Bug: #1389419
'}]
commit_message:
Remove test_barbican from keymgr tests

Unfortunately it seems we have some very poorly
written keymgr unit tests, specifically
keymgr/test_barbican.py does this:
from barbicanclient.common import auth

First problem is that from a unit test perspective
that pretty much sucks, second problem is that
barbicanclient as of version 3.0.0.0 no longer
has an "auth" module, as a result Cinderunit tests
now fail.

The test_barbican.py unit tests need to be rewritten
to mock out the client components and actually test
Cinder components where needed without relying on
the barbicanclient.

For now in order to free up the gate, remove test_barbican.py

Change-Id: Id770c87c0d622ae4c1e0d71141ffa9aed29be2ec

commit_message:
CDH Zookeeper Support

Sahara needs to support Zookeeper in CDH plugin. This proposal is
for a cdh cluster to support enabling Zookeeper service.

Change-Id: Iba89373ac4288bd36ed41024fd1aa4b97f77c9b0
Implements: blueprint cdh-zookeeper-support

commit_message:
Correct the README.md descriptions

Drops the 'from git' from many of the elements. This implies
that the elements always use git... which they don't if
you are using packages.

Also, expands many of the descriptions to say 'and configures' since
most of these elements also contain the OAC/ORC scripts to actually
configure things as well.

Change-Id: I3cbf80c99cfedd73770c9d24e140b7d2443f0dda

commit_message:
Add requirement for APIImpact flag

Adds a requirement for an APIImpact flag in
the commit message for a proposed spec if it proposes
changes to the Sahara REST API. This will make it
much easier for people such as the API WG who want to
review API changes across OpenStack to find and
review proposed API changes.

Change-Id: I5389802bc87001f20ba4a9c1e5a57fab624ac41a

commit_message:
Move puppet-tuskar to Stackforge

puppet-tuskar from eNovance repository to Stackforge which will be
supported by the puppet-openstack community. This patch integrate the
puppet module in all OpenStack infra workflow.

Change-Id: If52d2ea42a9d94789ec85675c1edae670f6e32a6

commit_message:
Allow creating branches for requests-mock

Give permission for the requests-mock-release group to create branches.
This may be used to do backports and bugfix releases.

Change-Id: I6ad3e8b1178bcb6fa6dc44694fb6a60fa52de2a7

Both reviews don't really overlap because the tox targets I use start only the functional tests suite for three drivers, and yours start the unit tests suite for amqp1.0."}, {'account_id': 6547, 'date': '2014-10-31 16:25:11.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 4:

Mehdi, have the oslo.messaging changes been merged? Please provide a link in the commit message to them, something like:

Depends on: XXX'}, {'account_id': 8770, 'date': '2014-10-31 19:20:22.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 4:

Those 'unit' tests (tox -eamqp1) are really _functional_ tests.  The tox testcases call the AMQP 1.0 Driver class api directly, with a simple loopback test broker attached via a local socket.  So in actuality Gordon's tests do cover these apis as well.

The primary reason I proposed running tox -eamqp1 under CI was that the packages necessary to run those tests aren't available on Ubuntu, so I couldn't have these tests run by default on a developer's machine when they ran tox (e.g. I can't put it in the default envlist).  Using CI, I could install all the needed packages via devstack first.  This would give us some protection from changes inadvertently breaking amqp1 support should the developer not be able to run 'tox -eamqp1'.

So I'm happy with just running Gordon's tests against amqp1 in CI, and eventually adding 'amqp1' to the default envlist when Ubuntu adopts the necessary packages.

I'm certainly open to alternatives, though! :)"}, {'account_id': 2813, 'date': '2014-11-03 06:47:40.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 5.'}, {'account_id': 2813, 'date': '2014-11-03 06:49:14.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 4:

@Ken, ok, so I have added the amqp1.0 tests into the py27-func-amqp1 target to ensure they are run until ubuntu get the proton packages.'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2014-11-03 06:51:39.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 5: Verified+1

commit_message:
oslo.messaging: Add experimental functional tests

This changes create 3 new jobs for oslo.messaging to
run the functional tests suite on 3 different drivers
rabbit, qpid and amqp 1.0.

Depends on: https://review.openstack.org/#/c/130437/

Change-Id: Ifa0561e24424b10a626e440d160b389a704f29eb

Hi Sam, Evgeny,

Please find my review comments below.

1. No CLI code is present in this request - is there another review for that? If so, please point to it as well.

2. There is no clear demarcation between SSL entities and LBaaS entities. For example, we see in lbaas_ssl_db.py, that class SSLPolicy has VIP related functions in it.Another example - create_ssl_*() functions are present in the lbaas plugin code (class LbaasSSLPluginBase(ServicePluginBase). The same is reflected in extensions/lbaas_ssl.py.

3. In this design, SSL entities are being treated as inherent to LBaaS. Is this always the case? One use case of a non-LBaaS/neutron dependency on an SSL certificate would be nova wanting to associate a VM with an SSL certificate so it could push it into an apache configuration. Another would be a custom service VM that would want to do the same with any other application, including a loadbalancer.

4. The ideal place to place SSL entities would be keystone, as first class citizens/resources, and have all other openstack components simply maintain mappings of the SSL entities IDs with their own entities (like a vip-SSLcert mapping, vip-VMid mapping and so on).

5. The current approach is implementing SSL within the scope/extensions of LBaaS. If and when we move SSL entities to keystone later, it would be much easier to refactor the code if the code is more object oriented now. We dont have to expose any APIs to directly manipulate SSL entities for now in that case - we can put those in only when the functionality is moved to keystone. If we want to limit the scope of SSL within lbaas, dont expose CLIs/APIs like neutron ssl-*-CRUD. Make it neutron lb-ssl-*-CRUD.


5. It is understandable that for now, the certs will be stored in the db. However, barbican could be the preferred storage for certs going forward. In this commit, it looks like we arent fully accounting for future changes where we would need to provide a choice between mysql or another store for certs and keys, like barbican or HSM etc. We should at least provide some neutron wide configuration to allow the cloud admin to specify this store. So we could place such a param (say key_cert_driver to point to the class that implements specific logic to talk to the key storage mechanism, followed by any necessary credentials/ip etc)  in neutron.conf, and in neutron/services/loadbalancer/plugin.py, for each of the CRUD functions, we must put in code that chooses a driver based on these params.


Thanks,
Regards,
Vijay'}, {'account_id': 8446, 'date': '2014-05-01 15:50:16.000000000', 'content': 'Restored'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2014-05-01 15:50:17.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 6: -Verified

commit_message:
(WIP, do not review) New SSL extension

Note: This change is a continuation of a previous change
that was abandoned due to rebase issues (https://review.openstack.org/#/c/63510)

Adding new ssl extension for ssl-termination support
in neutron.
Extension is served by lbaas plugin
and is extending lbaas vip with ssl entities associations
For this to work, I changed the new resource_helper module
to get attributes from the attributes module where it's actually
updated by the attributes extension mechanism

Creating new abstract driver for ssl api
Adding new absract driver as a base to radware driver

Adding ssl dbmixin for ssl policies and certificates
management.
If service provider (driver) is not inheriting from new
abstract ssl driver - new "ExtensionNotSupportedByProvider"
exception is raised.

Since association of ssl certificates and vip requires
sending a list on certificates, list support was needed
in neutron resource attributes parsing mechanism.
I added the lists support and extended unit tests to test it.

Added unit tests for extension and db mixin

Alembic migration was added for the change

Radware driver and its unit tests are WIP, do not review.

Change-Id: I8c8f44b315da4b050882685e5411d714439b8fe9
Implements: blueprint lbaas-ssl-termination

commit_message:
Bump testtools version to support message parameter in assertIn

Commit aa67a51299faa5e51da2e96fcf3b0ba3fc2ddc86 introduced usage of the
`message` parameter to `assertIn`.

The current minimium version of `testtools` doesn't support it, so we need to
bump up to at least version 0.3.6.

Change-Id: I6985bd1daa373348f2f37e26fb5597ac3e46f316
Closes-Bug: 1387870

commit_message:
Disable python-barbicanclient 3.0.0 (only) version

python-barbicanclient 3.0.0 has introduced cliff module, but pins it
to 1.6.1, while global-requirements set it to >=1.7.0, now the whole
OpenStack projects depends on higher version of cliff, but
python-barbicanclient is needed by cinder, then grenade test will
fail because: pkg_resources.DistributionNotFound: cliff==1.6.1

As long as python-barbicanclient maintainers don't provide a patch
for 3.0.0 (which seems not happen FMPOV), we need to disbable this
version.
This rule will not block usage of 3.0.1.

Change-Id: Idd519fc3aa6e004aa75b56b36ffd125dde20f70e
Related-Bug: #1388414
(cherry picked from commit 76f294a13558fbbacdad394e91956f8872746ce7)

commit_message:
Set vif_details to reflect enable_security_group

While plugging vif, VIFDriver in Nova follows "ovs_hybrid_plug" and
"port_filter" in "binding:vif_detail" which is passed from Neutron, but
those are always true.  This patch make ML2 OVS mech driver set those
param depends on enable_security_group flag.  It enables users to avoid
ovs_hybrid plugging.

This patch also fixes the same issue in the following plugins/drivers:
  * NEC Plugin
  * BigSwitch Plugin
  * Ryu Plugin
  * ML2 Plugin - OFAgent Mech Driver

Closes-Bug: #1336624
Change-Id: I2b7fb526a6f1b730ad65289307b24fd28b996e1b

Thank you for your first contribution to OpenStack.

    Your patch will now be tested automatically by OpenStack testing frameworks
    and once the automatic tests pass, it will be reviewed by other friendly
    developers. They will give you feedback and may require you to refine it.

    People seldom get their patch approved on the first try, so don't be
    concerned if requested to make corrections. Feel free to modify your patch
    and resubmit a new change-set.

    Patches usually take 3 to 7 days to be reviewed so be patient and be
    available on IRC to ask and answer questions about your work. The more you
    participate in the community the more rewarding it is for you. You may also
    notice that the more you get to know people and get to be known, the faster
    your patches will be reviewed and eventually approved. Get to know others
    and become known by doing code reviews: anybody can do it, and it's a
    great way to learn the code base.

commit_message:
Containers created by Freezer will have freezer_ as prefix

The containers used by freezer to executed backups needs to have
freezer_ prefix in the name. If the user provider container doesn't
have the prefix, it is automatically added also to the container
segments name. This is done to quickly identify the containers

Added --path-to-backup to the existing ones (-F, --file-to-backup)
as can be more intuitive for the user

Bumped version to: 1.1.0 as 1.0.9-2 is now tagged in upstream

Change-Id: I891391ea07f75b5dcdc43d9b1d65a75837065f30
LAUNCHPAD: https://blueprints.launchpad.net/freezer/+spec/freezer-containers

commit_message:
Disable HAProxy MySQL backup on controller0

Configure controller0 (the bootstrap-host) so that it is never
an HAProxy backup node for MySQL. This avoids MySQL deadlocking.

Closes-Bug: 1387685
Depends-On: I811707c729b1cf3a48330cee976f8430a8d168f2
Change-Id: I6fc091efba347da13f7fc28240fcbf6c7fc2bc12

commit_message:
Disable HAProxy MySQL backup on controller0

Configure controller0 (the bootstrap-host) so that it is never
an HAProxy backup node for MySQL. This avoids MySQL deadlocking.

For this change to apply, tripleo-incubator needs to be changed
so that controller0HAProxyMySQLParams is passed to Heat as blank
in devtest_overcloud.sh.

Partial-Bug: 1387685
Change-Id: I811707c729b1cf3a48330cee976f8430a8d168f2

commit_message:
Use keystone v3 and get a project scoped token

Change to use the keystone v3 client. Rename os-tenant-id to
os-project id and os-tenant-name to os-project-name to match
keystone v3

Validate token is a project scoped token if the token is
fetched using user and password and not passed in

Allow the user to specify os-domain-name or os-domain-id if
needed to resolve os-project-name

Change-Id: I19fe2d9af5f0f862303066bb235826373e6d605f

commit_message:
Make sysctl net.ipv4.ip_forward def safe

When using puppet-nova with another big Puppet modules
this sysctl may be defined before.

The solution is to make a definition safe.

Closes-bug: #1384145

Change-Id: I4d28f277bccd16f3719a4806e641461df3749518

commit_message:
Fix the argument order for openstack client

If there are --xxx argument placed for openstack clients such as
nova, glance, keystone etc, these arguments need to be placed before
the actual command line. Otherwise, the client will raise unrecognized
arguments exception which will make the command execution fail.

Change-Id: I1568f9332accffdfa3a34d8bbd842f707b1a340e
Closes-Bug: #1388147

Since there are many problems when applying cinder v2 api, like
cannot attach volumes to VM from nova, and there may be other
problems in glance, the integration of cinder v2 api and
other services is not well tested and the related configurations
are not clear. We'd better revert the cinder api version back to
v1 before all things are clear.

This patch may break cookbook-openstack-block-storage unless the
patch https://review.openstack.org/#/c/132517/ is merged.

Closes-bug: #1388741
Change-Id: I39cd138fe7cb6fe685df12403ff81aad8906d134
"}]
commit_message:
Change the specs for reverting cinder api to v1

Since there are many problems when applying cinder v2 api, like
cannot attach volumes to VM from nova, and there may be other
problems in glance, the integration of cinder v2 api and
other services is not well tested and the related configurations
are not clear. We'd better revert the cinder api version back to
v1 before all things are clear.

This patch may break cookbook-openstack-block-storage unless the
patch https://review.openstack.org/#/c/132517/ is merged.

Closes-bug: #1388741
Change-Id: I39cd138fe7cb6fe685df12403ff81aad8906d134

commit_message:
Use revision head instead of juno to populate the Neutron database scheme

Using juno as revision is not working:

ERROR [alembic.util] No such revision 'juno'
  FAILED: No such revision 'juno'

Remove the note that the database population occurs later because the
server and plugin configuration is already complete.

Change-Id: Ibb8a606803edd77d4bd3b07bf7d070a04ed69fa1

When I wrote in the last patchset that this class could be turned into a purely classmethod-class (namespace-ish), the design I had in mind was that the relevant outputs (what you called here vf_section and help_command_output) will be returned to the calling function, and will be passed as a parameter throughout the functions.

In the current state, the class behaves like a non-static class that has non-static variables (ie. vf_section, help_command_output), but is in fact static.

I will be really happy if you could look into my suggested design and see if it works for you. Sorry again for all the loops I'm putting you through."}, {'account_id': 6598, 'date': '2014-09-29 06:17:09.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 10:

Hi John,
Before pushing next patch-set, I would like to check with you the following design. The class with have three API methods:
1. get_ip_link_output(root_helper) => returns 'ip link help' content
2. get_vf_mgmt_section(output) => extracts the vf section from the output (1)
3. vf_mgmt_cap_supported(vf_section, cap, subcap) => checks for given capability (sub-capability) support in given vf_section

Is it what you had in mind?"}, {'account_id': 12444, 'date': '2014-09-29 08:07:19.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 10:

Sounds about right.

Looking at the design you wrote, you could even lower the number of methods to 3 - get_vf_mgmt_section() could use get_ip_link_output() directly and return the vf section so the user could use. This way, the user will have to use get_vf_mgmt_section() to run 'ip link help' and extract from it the relevant section (which the user will save for as long as he needs), and then vf_mgmt_cap_supported().

The reason for that, I think, is that the user won't have anything "special" to do with get_ip_link_output()'s output. Can you think of a usage a calling function could do with this string object? If not then it's probably not needed outside get_vf_mgmt_section().'}, {'account_id': 6598, 'date': '2014-09-29 09:28:57.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 11.'}, {'account_id': 6598, 'date': '2014-09-29 09:31:53.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 11:

commit_message:
Detect if iproute2 support SR-IOV commands

Add sanity_check that 'ip link' command supports VF management and
link state changes of VF by parsing 'ip link help' command output.

Co-authored-by: Samer Deeb <samerd@mellanox.com>
Closes bug: 1349302

Change-Id: I5a72a9061a76c39960076f078905371f07069431

in the groups list) we should avoid failing when getting
members of that group in the running of watches function and

'}, {'created': '2014-11-04 07:48:56.000000000', 'message': 'Handle when a group used to exist but no longer does

When a group used to exist (or for some reason still exists
in the groups list) we should avoid failing when getting
members of that group in the running of watches function and

Change-Id: I5484857e6ea58f1cdec5f9f8fac69a3571e053ed

commit_message:
Handle when a group used to exist but no longer does

When a group used to exist (or for some reason still exists
in the groups list) we should avoid failing when getting
members of that group in the running of watches function and
should instead handle that case specially and trigger all
watches (to notify those watches that everyone was removed).

Change-Id: I5484857e6ea58f1cdec5f9f8fac69a3571e053ed

commit_message:
Multi driver support to VPN agent

Add multi driver support to the recipe of vpn_agent,
by changing vpn_device_driver option from string to list.
And add a new option named vpn_device_driver_packages to
install package dependencies according vpn_device_driver.

DocImpact
Closes-Bug: #1386067
Closes-Bug: #1386070
Change-Id: If84827e421a2d94b5ae802a65b3d906670e28e90

commit_message:
Add glance_ca_certificates_file

This commit adds glance_ca_certificates_file into cinder.conf.
It is used for glance client requests.

Change-Id: I4449ce8ec67af70463fd2107749a555c634767d8
Closes-Bug: #1389071

commit_message:
Revert the default cinder api version to v1

Since there are many problems when applying cinder v2 api, like
cannot attach volumes to VM from nova, and there may be other
problems in glance, the integration of cinder v2 api and
other services is not well tested and the related configurations
are not clear yet. We'd better revert the cinder api version back
to v1 before all things are clear.

Closes-bug: #1388741
Change-Id: Ic27a437be3c45e8a522c9c50b1e658de4ee79e94

commit_message:
Fix .push python-ibm-db-django polluting common attribute

A Common attribute was having a dashboard specific package added to it.
This has side effects as it will effect other cookbooks using that
attribute.

* Create attrbute to hold dashboard specific database packages
* Tests unchanged as they are still correct outcome

Change-Id: I99768ae91ed0db9f632d2529014130c38096f8fe
Closes-Bug: #1364508

commit_message:
Add options to enable using DHCP agent Metadata-proxy

Add options to support DHCP agent providing metadata-proxy.
In some cases, users have to disable L3 Agent. But people still
need metadata services.

Change-Id: I4664fc3a4937c3b7b5c27e74f509b683ffbedd09

- noop http://logs.openstack.org/79/114179/2/check/noop/1ec08f3 : SUCCESS'}, {'account_id': 406, 'date': '2014-08-27 08:01:05.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2:

I do not think we should approach issues this way. Tests are intended to only test object under testing, without attempts to restart it to make it work.

Ceph should handle clock desync after time was synced. If it doesn't, I would say that it is Ceph issue. I can easily imagine situation of this kind in real life. Server was off for some time, then it was powered on - and there is clock desync. It will be synced over a few hours or less by NTP, and if I need to restart ceph service to recover dead osd - it is obviously an issue. It should be picked up automatically by Ceph.

Clock syncing from tests is fine as it quickly prepares environment to the correct state, which would be in a real deployment, and then we test other entities on this environment (like Ceph)."}, {'account_id': 8787, 'date': '2014-08-27 20:10:21.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2:

Mike has a point: an environment in which all Ceph services have been restarted is not a valid test target for tests that are supposed to test a fresh deployment. It doesn't invalidate the test altogether (you wouldn't expect a Ceph service to never ever be restarted in a long-lived production environment), but it introduces a possibility to miss a rare category of bugs that are present immediately after deployment, but disappear if Ceph services are restart.

On the other hand, the problem with Ceph time handling when running inside a VM is a fundamental limitation that upstream developers do not intend to address. They run their tests on real hardware, and redeploy from scratch (instead of reverting a snapshot) before each test run.

Disabling cephx authentication (add "auth = none" to ceph.conf) is another option at working around this problem, cephx is very time sensitive and the most likely cause of osd breakage on clock skew.

Finally, in some cases OSDs can recover from temporary clock skew, we should experiment with sleep here and see if giving Ceph cluster enough time after resume is also likely to make the problem go away.'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2014-10-27 14:30:19.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2: Verified-1

Merge Failed.

This change was unable to be automatically merged with the current state of the repository. Please rebase your change and upload a new patchset.'}, {'account_id': 8787, 'date': '2014-10-31 23:11:37.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2: Code-Review-1'}, {'account_id': 11081, 'date': '2014-11-04 10:00:22.000000000', 'content': 'Abandoned'}]

commit_message:
Restart Ceph if some OSDs are dead after revert

In system tests after VMs snapshot reverting Ceph reports
that some OSDs are dead and doesn't recover them authomatically.
We should try to restart Ceph service on failed node in order
to workaround this issue.

Change-Id: I107213fbc77d4ef1830e19fe682bcc5ecee885ab
Closes-bug: #1356773

Handle exception better in v2.1 attach_interface

Add more information when exception occurs in attach interface at Nova
v2.1 API layer.
The commit I7402cfc28d4ee7989c7eb054556df57918bbaeee has been merged
for v2.0 API, this patch does the same change for v2.1 API.

Partially implements blueprint v2-on-v3-api

[{'created': '2014-11-01 16:39:34.000000000', 'message': 'libvirt: safe_decode domain.XMLDesc(0) for i18n logging

domain.XMLDesc(0) can return a utf-8 encoded string which will cause a
UnicodeDecodeError when substituting the variable in the _LE unicode
translated Message object in oslo.i18n.

This change simply decodes domain.XMLDesc(0) before passing it onto the
logging method when used with a translated message.

Closes-Bug: #1388386

Change-Id: Id56d6564cfb15cc479e664020ae6f1c82acacb09
'}]
commit_message:
libvirt: safe_decode domain.XMLDesc(0) for i18n logging

domain.XMLDesc(0) can return a utf-8 encoded string which will cause a
UnicodeDecodeError when substituting the variable in the _LE unicode
translated Message object in oslo.i18n.

This change simply decodes domain.XMLDesc(0) before passing it onto the
logging method when used with a translated message.

Closes-Bug: #1388386

Change-Id: Id56d6564cfb15cc479e664020ae6f1c82acacb09

commit_message:
Don't hardcode glance protocol when finding trove guest image

This allows configuration of trove when devstack is configured
for SSL or tls-proxy.

Change-Id: I680effda94926951f9068e2df1e354c708aa4495

commit_message:
Add requirement for APIImpact flag

Adds a requirement for an APIImpact flag in
the commit message for a proposed spec if it proposes
changes to the Ironic REST API. This will make it
much easier for people such as the API WG who want to
review API changes across OpenStack to find and
review proposed API changes.

Change-Id: I6973077d0b8d491e03a6e093dcc5e309395f2c07

commit_message:
Provide a helper function to extract a given parameters value

Instead of having logic exist to fetch all the parameters values
for all parameter names add a helper function that can extract
just a single parameters value/s. This is useful for at least tooz
which is doing a similar logic in an awkward manner (by always
accessing the [-1] index of parameter values).

Change-Id: Ia9dd314e7b78d531b0cf7f96bcc294acb964e0e0

commit_message:
Change CLI tests to use auth providers

This commit changes the CLI tests to use the auth providers for
credentials. Previously they were just using the admin credentials
straight from the config file. The typical motivation for doing this
would be tenant isolation for running in parallel, but that doesn't
apply to the CLI tests because they are simple read-only. However, in
the future when test-accounts supports admin credentials doing this
won't be supported.

Change-Id: Iad5fe6e8abe4491d10e9a676a1c2a7da05a38113

commit_message:
Move generate_glance_url into image.api

We moved glance call into image.api as cinder and neutron in this
release. So it would be better to move all glance related calls
into image api. This patch moves generate_glance_url into image api.

Change-Id: I9cd29f946495d6a74edb3eb125f5d10ae6b04e3b

commit_message:
More timesync tries after snapshot is reverted

Currently only 3 tries are performed with 30 sec timeout,
but it is not enough in certain situations for time sync.

Change-Id: I8739cdd0d92f6daca8d8415cb806c0ea7c2f7883
Closes-Bug: #1388212

commit_message:
More timesync tries after snapshot is reverted

Currently only 3 tries are performed with 30 sec timeout,
but it is not enough in certain situations for time sync.

Change-Id: I460f86ebbf59f32c9288889eb76bdc9a472d4a07
Closes-Bug: #1388212

commit_message:
Make test_security_groups nose compatible

With nose, `TestNeutronSecurityGroupRulesBase` will be picked up as an actual
test because it starts with `Test`. Since this is an abstract class, we should
prefix it with an underscore so we don't run those tests directly, rather, run
them in their concrete subclasses instead.

Change-Id: Ifa96152ef71b2b27d8b8c76e25a4136186831032

commit_message:
Use haproxy httpchk to detect a radosgw crash

TCP check by itself is only able to confirm that the Apache process is
still there and listening on port 6780, an HTTP GET request will get a
response code 500 when there is no radosgw process behind Apache, and
haproxy will mark such host as DOWN.

Change-Id: Iee8e02427d58befa51596867a5c4c623ee0ddbe8
Closes-Bug: #1385002
(cherry picked from commit 151ca375000faad75c92a709dee969f0caaeb18b)

revisions:
[{'created': '2014-10-21 16:33:08.000000000', 'message': 'Set <host> in cinder.conf to rbd:<pool> for RBD backend

Cinder volume can only be managed by a cinder-volume process that has <host>
configuration variable value matching <os-vol-host-attr:host> attribute of the
volume.

By default, host of a cinder-volume service is set to its hostname, which means
that if one controller is lost, none of its volumes can be managed by
cinder-volume processes on other controllers. This makes sense for Cinder LVM,
but not for RBD or other shared backends.

This commit sets <host> to the same value on all controllers when RBD backend
is enabled, so that any controller can manage RBD backed volumes created by any
other controller.

Change-Id: I47161796dbb817eab026402760799bee24371863
Partial-Bug: #1371328
'}]
commit_message:
Set <host> in cinder.conf to rbd:<pool> for RBD backend

Cinder volume can only be managed by a cinder-volume process that has <host>
configuration variable value matching <os-vol-host-attr:host> attribute of the
volume.

By default, host of a cinder-volume service is set to its hostname, which means
that if one controller is lost, none of its volumes can be managed by
cinder-volume processes on other controllers. This makes sense for Cinder LVM,
but not for RBD or other shared backends.

This commit sets <host> to the same value on all controllers when RBD backend
is enabled, so that any controller can manage RBD backed volumes created by any
other controller.

Change-Id: I47161796dbb817eab026402760799bee24371863
Partial-Bug: #1371328

[{'created': '2014-10-31 17:25:20.000000000', 'message': "Make test_quotas compatible with nosetests

Nosetests detects any function that ends with `test` as a test function which
causes `is_v20_api_test` to be run as a test. This fails because `plugin`
won't be defined yet.

In the interest of being developer friendly and supporting this common
test-runner, we should prefix with an underscore so it doesn't get picked up
as an actual test.

Change-Id: I0802b9f2271cc6f555a409784cfb52911098c2d6
"}]
commit_message:
Make test_quotas compatible with nosetests

Nosetests detects any function that ends with `test` as a test function which
causes `is_v20_api_test` to be run as a test. This fails because `plugin`
won't be defined yet.

In the interest of being developer friendly and supporting this common
test-runner, we should prefix with an underscore so it doesn't get picked up
as an actual test.

Change-Id: I0802b9f2271cc6f555a409784cfb52911098c2d6

commit_message:
Fix public VIP gateway ping for neutron

We have different network scheme in astute.yaml for neutron. This
patch fixes public gateway calculation for pacemaker "ping"
resource when we use neutron.

Closes-bug: 1373375
Change-Id: Ia49ba52d3eab5dd5733450901e7a84a3448dbd3d
(cherry picked from commit c08179f54be64de410ef0f54a49b3bd28b0f2f3b)

(1 comment)

We usually use a status code to check what happen in servers.
IMO, so API docs should have a reason why servers return the status code.'}, {'account_id': 2622, 'date': '2014-09-11 14:57:13.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

Of course we still use status codes: 2xx means success, 4xx means the client made an error, and 5xx means the server made an error.

The intention of this change is to stop documenting specific success codes, because Swift doesn't guarantee them. Swift follows HTTP semantics as best it can, and HTTP defines success as above, so that's what should be in the document."}, {'account_id': 964, 'date': '2014-09-11 18:49:15.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1: Code-Review-2

I'm really not happy with documenting a range of 200-200 inclusive, and the code patch itself hasn't landed. Marking -2 until this is resolved."}, {'account_id': 5803, 'date': '2014-09-11 19:22:07.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

What about specifying only 200-206, the codes specified in the rfc2616.'}, {'account_id': 8878, 'date': '2014-09-12 08:41:19.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

@Samuel
You mean swift will return different response codes in same situation, aren't you?

For example:
The document says shows details for an account API (GET /v1/{account}) returns 204 if the account has no container.
But your patch says the API returns not only 204 but 200, 202, etc in the condition.

I'm not able to find out if the account has some containers or not by response code.
So the document has to have a description of conditions why the response is returned at least."}, {'account_id': 2448, 'date': '2014-09-14 00:10:57.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Code-Review-1

(4 comments)'}, {'account_id': 330, 'date': '2014-09-14 00:17:02.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

How about this for a compromise: Document the codes that Swift does return, but specifically and explicitly mention that clients should respond to status code classes rather than specific codes.

Does that makes sense and satisfy everyone? I think this is much more along the lines of what we're trying to get done."}, {'account_id': 6167, 'date': '2014-09-15 14:25:03.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Code-Review-1

As a developer working for REST API, I can understand that developers want to change the success codes to more accurate codes if they find. However, what should we expect to clients with such success code changes?

If we cannot promise stable success codes, clients cannot handle such success codes even if swift provides accurate codes. Clients should expect the success codes as unstable and they cannot switch their behaviors based on the success codes. That seems a dilemma.'}, {'account_id': 612, 'date': '2014-10-03 05:36:53.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

Hi, just pinging this patch since it hasn't moved in a couple of weeks. Do you want to continue discussion on the mailing list?"}, {'account_id': 612, 'date': '2014-11-02 14:54:11.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

Hi, pinging this again. Any movement?'}, {'account_id': 2622, 'date': '2014-11-03 20:27:40.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

I thought this would be an easy, non-controversial change. Swift developers have only ever promised HTTP semantics: "success" means "status code in range 200 to 299". I was simply trying to make the docs match the promises.

I don't want a mailing-list thread with all the attendant nitpicking, bikeshedding, accidental misunderstandings, deliberate misunderstandings, scope creep (operators ML! surveys! focus groups!), and unending pontification about how this affects all of OpenStack holistically. The mere thought of that literally makes me irritable and jumpy.

If fixing the docs requires that level of discussion from that large a group of people, then it's not worth it. I'll just abandon this because the cost is too high.'}, {'account_id': 2622, 'date': '2014-11-03 20:27:43.000000000', 'content': 'Abandoned'}]
revisions:
[{'created': '2014-09-10 23:55:09.000000000', 'message': 'Replace specific success codes with 2xx for Swift

Swift has never specified particular success codes. Instead, it relies
on HTTP's definition of success, which is simply any status code where
200 <= status <= 299.

There's some discussion over at https://review.openstack.org/117193
about this. In particular, a quote from the Swift PTL: "To be very
clear, Swift's policy is and always has been to respond with 2xx
series on success, 4xx series on client error, and 5xx on server
error."

Change-Id: Id68154bc500489ba2f9e16323ec7e441eb384104
'}]
commit_message:
Replace specific success codes with 2xx for Swift

Swift has never specified particular success codes. Instead, it relies
on HTTP's definition of success, which is simply any status code where
200 <= status <= 299.

There's some discussion over at https://review.openstack.org/117193
about this. In particular, a quote from the Swift PTL: "To be very
clear, Swift's policy is and always has been to respond with 2xx
series on success, 4xx series on client error, and 5xx on server
error."

Change-Id: Id68154bc500489ba2f9e16323ec7e441eb384104

Use properties in alarm expression parser

Change to use @properties in alarm expression parser instead of getters/setters.
More idiomatically correct for python.

commit_message:
Add initial section for SambaFS vol driver

A SambaFS driver for cinder volumes was added in Juno.
This patch adds a stub section to the configuration reference
so its options can be easily found.

Change-Id: Ib08c839077ee52d380f7040e7f682ca6a78278bd
Closes-Bug: 1367345

commit_message:
Add cacert and insecure arguments for get tenant id call

If keystone are configured with SSL, neutron need to connect keystone
with certs(or insecure) to load the admin_tenant_id. This commit will
add these arguments for the call.

Related openstack-common cookbook fix:
https://review.openstack.org/#/c/132282/

Closes-Bug: #1388138

commit_message:
Only sysctl reserverd ports when available.

Only set the keystone reserved ports when available, on some system
(like when running under containers) where this sysfs interface is not
exposed we are almost pretty sure these ports would be exclusive for our
devstack.

Change-Id: I06d7d227ae94d564c91c16119e4bbbcc6564a280

commit_message:
Add a minimum redis version check while starting

To avoid having the redis driver connecting to a
very old redis we should try to be defensive and
raise an exception if we are connecting to a redis
version that will just not provide enough working
functionality for this driver to work correctly.

Change-Id: Ic16990805d8ac015f2c1f12f44e4115dba366135

commit_message:
Try to use PSETEX when possible

In order to provide more accurate heartbeating expiry we should
try to use the PSETEX command when we can (which supports millisecond
resolution expiry instead of using the SETEX which only supports
second level expiry).

Change-Id: I4f6e6b20ec26d9da03caf508c8e6b4c54c156f93

If we got kicked out of a group, or the group got removed
we don't need to log a warning when stopping and an error
related to the above occurs.

Change-Id: Iccadd6483b7e75d1b1ce3c4e6904a22380af7f1c
"}]
commit_message:
Avoid logging warnings when group deleted or member gone

If we got kicked out of a group, or the group got removed
we don't need to log a warning when stopping and an error
related to the above occurs.

Change-Id: Iccadd6483b7e75d1b1ce3c4e6904a22380af7f1c

commit_message:
Correct docker plugin setup in README.md

When we use heat default plugin directories, we should link docker
plugin module directory instead of docker plugin directory. When we
define our own heat plugin directories, we should add docker plugin
directory into plugin_dirs.

And add check section.

commit_message:
Set nginx default settings for master node

- increase number of workers from 2 to half available CPUs.
- enable epoll by default
- enable tcpnopush
- enable tcpnodelay
- disable server_token

These settings allow to bootstrap many nodes in parallel allowing
anaconda and debian installer to get all files without timeout.

Partial-Bug: 1384510
Partial-Bug: 1349360

Change-Id: I44054cf2afa1fa5a70ba064f4957b964947b2b2c
Implements: blueprint 100-nodes-support
Signed-off-by: Sergii Golovatiuk <sgolovatiuk@mirantis.com>

commit_message:
Workaround for negative vals in total*Used in nova absolute_limits

Due to bug 1370867 there is a case where negative values are returned
in total*Used in absolute_limits. If it occurs, Horizon Overview page
cannot be displayed due to an error "cannot convert float infinity to
integer". This commit replaces negative values in total*Used with 0
for a workarond.

Conflicts:
	openstack_dashboard/test/api_tests/nova_tests.py

Change-Id: I606803bdff1d335cc9f92d67619ff82f356a5143
Closes-Bug: #1370869
(cherry picked from commit d49ad74e280f9b7d9397e951f12dc428f26821df)

Could we set the OPENSTACK_KEYSTONE_ADMIN_ROLE to be a list? In a cloud configuration where I want to split the global role admin to cloud_admin and domain_admin roles ( https://review.openstack.org/#/c/123509/4/etc/policy.cloudsample.json ), I would like to give permission to all of them to, for example, list users and projects ( for more information: https://blueprints.launchpad.net/horizon/+spec/admin-rbac ).
Also, In my opinion, the Admin dashboard isn't taking into account the policies, what I see is that the Horizon "knows" which operations are for admin, not checking t into the policies, for example list instances, list images, list flavors, etc, are admin operations. It doesn't take into account that someone could configure a cloud that defines the operation to list flavor to any member on it.
Another observation is that the panels in the Admin dashboard are visible only if the user has access to that service. Even if the user doesn't has the permission to do any operation in that panel it'll be shown. In the blueprint linked above, I suggest that instead of checking if the user has access to the service, we should check if the user has permission to do the operation. For example, Images Panel in Admin Dashboard is shown if the user can access Glance service, instead of that, we should check if the user has permission to do any CRUD operation with images.'}, {'account_id': 13325, 'date': '2014-10-10 10:02:03.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 6:

@Andre Aranha	
I think that converting OPENSTACK_KEYSTONE_ADMIN_ROLE to the list could be a realy good idea, thank you for describing your usecase.
As for your suggestions in the mentioned blueprint implement rbac support for identity, I think it would be better to discuss the implementation on the blueprints whiteboard.
Howewer, I'm not shure that the implementation of the two blueprints in one patch is a good idea."}, {'account_id': 13325, 'date': '2014-10-16 16:15:03.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 7.'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2014-10-16 18:01:10.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 7: Verified-1

commit_message:
Remove admin role name 'admin' hardcode in User.is_superuser()

Because of hardcoding name as the 'admin' was impossible to
use administrative panel with a custom administrative role name.
This fix replaces hardcoded the name of the administrative role
with the Horizon settings constant with list of roles.
So, now administrative roles can be multiple.
Related commit: https://review.openstack.org/#/c/123741/

Change-Id: I04277cd50a938f02949ae0e33228e1628197d252
Partial-Bug: #1161144

commit_message:
Handle negative values in total*Used for Cinder absolute limits

In some cases negative values can be returned for resources currently
in use. When this occurs, the project overview page fails with an
error 500 due to an OverflowError, "cannot convert float infinity to
integer". Handle this case more gracefully.

Change-Id: Id1ad16eafdde906dc74bfafc7f72ea8d3bdcdc8f
Closes-Bug: #1386687
(cherry picked from commit 53c7dc022ed4e0d5d60fb344b3e8c94e3dfb7d43)

commit_message:
Inaccurate description found in keystone's docs

- No permission to make changes on dist-packages or site-packages by default.
- The link will be made in the dist-packages instead of site-packages.

Change-Id: I4c937f6a91cec76f9c9c421bbb6ce31f4119268a

I would recommend to consider the inclusion of Security logging guidelines as part of this.'}, {'account_id': 2750, 'date': '2014-04-30 20:35:58.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

(1 comment)'}, {'account_id': 1699, 'date': '2014-04-30 21:06:28.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

Basically I love the blueprints thrust.

I'd love to see a real spec for how to construct a proper openstack logging event, and how to place those events into the message queue for consumption.  Something that's more engineering spec then proverb.

That being said, a couple of things I'd like to see that I didn't see in there just yet.  ( mind you i may have missed it, i am human after all )

1.  Standardized Metadata

Being able to parse a log for content with a known metadata structure would be very helpful for folks planning on consuming logs in adaptive orchestration scenarios.

2.  Message Service Etiquette

I think the 'logged events need to make sense' starts to get into the idea of a common logging etiquette.  But there's the logical aspect beyond the aesthetic.  I assume we'll probably want to force rate limiting of logging should something start getting noisy.  I feel like that's something that should be done before hitting the message bus and creating noise there.  Specifically I am thinking of the repetition of messages being condensed on the app side before being pushed to the bus. 

This of course calls into question should this ettiquette be different for a WARN versus an ERROR?

3.  Audit Log Handling

This is probably outside scope.  Feel free to declare it so.  But once we start talking audit logs we need to discuss what can and cannot be done to an event before it gets signed ( yeah that would need to be discussed too ) and handed off to the audit log pipeline ( that doesn't exist yet ).

-Matt"}, {'account_id': 7677, 'date': '2014-04-30 21:11:27.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

(4 comments)

Some comments.  I love the idea, but there's a couple points I disagree with (posted inline)."}, {'account_id': 597, 'date': '2014-05-01 01:51:31.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

It seems to me that Swift can only comply with this if direct logging to files is finally implemented. Currently it has a gazillion processes that are not started by one parent and thus cannot share a log file easily, so it punts to syslog. And syslog adds format limitations. commit_message:
Log Guidelines

Draft logging guidelines for OpenStack. We're using the nova-specs
repository here to gather feedback pre-summit, and pre-deciding
on a cross project approach to guidelines like this. Nova is also
a natural starting point as there are contributors interested in
cleaning up Nova during Juno cycle.

Part of bp:log-guidelines

Change-Id: I674966988ed501dee323a106b84b5b6602d846b1

commit_message:
USe `trueorfalse` for INSTALL_TESTONLY_PACKAGES

INSTALL_TESTONLY_PACKAGES is assumed to be set to `True` or `False`.
However, in devstack-gate this variable is set to 0 or 1. The patch uses
the already existing `trueorfalse` function to evaluate
INSTALL_TESTONLY_PACKAGES and normalize its value.

Change-Id: I0e4a31e422bad2a31d919d9f871e24833a0faa99

commit_message:
Set permissions on sahara cache

Signing certificate directory should have 700 mode.
Before the change it was created with 755.

As a visual impact this CR removes warning from 
keystonemiddleware.

Change-Id: I8483e73447348b9a9e33dfd382543978a70a9d43
Closes-Bug: #1387416

[{'created': '2014-10-31 05:30:25.000000000', 'message': 'Workaround openrc failure on zsh

The recent GIT_DEPTH change introduced a [[ ]] construct
which doesn't work for zsh 5.0.2.  Workaround it by tweaking the test.

The following is a demonstration to show how zsh behaves:

    % if [[ "" ]];then echo hoge;fi
    zsh: parse error near `]]'
    % if [[ "x" ]];then echo hoge;fi
    zsh: parse error near `]]'
    % if [[ -n "" ]];then echo hoge;fi
    % if [[ -n "x" ]];then echo hoge;fi
    hoge
    %

Closes-Bug: #1387943
Change-Id: Ia88de876dacb3664a7c3d8f5a035e8e50fddb678
'}]
commit_message:
Workaround openrc failure on zsh

The recent GIT_DEPTH change introduced a [[ ]] construct
which doesn't work for zsh 5.0.2.  Workaround it by tweaking the test.

The following is a demonstration to show how zsh behaves:

    % if [[ "" ]];then echo hoge;fi
    zsh: parse error near `]]'
    % if [[ "x" ]];then echo hoge;fi
    zsh: parse error near `]]'
    % if [[ -n "" ]];then echo hoge;fi
    % if [[ -n "x" ]];then echo hoge;fi
    hoge
    %

Closes-Bug: #1387943
Change-Id: Ia88de876dacb3664a7c3d8f5a035e8e50fddb678

commit_message:
Add iptables rule for Ironic VMs -> Swift

The agent ramdisk gets instance images from swift, set firewall
rules to allow this.

Also configure Ironic API port using the correct variable, and
use SWIFT_DEFAULT_BIND_PORT for Swift ports everywhere.

Change-Id: Ieec8cc64e504b04a21daa49e90e2d4925f4838ee

commit_message:
Allow ceilometer to use redis for coordination

If redis is desired by local.conf via CEILOMETER_COORDINATION_URL
then make sure redis is installed and restarted.

commit_message:
Check DNS resolution in nodepool ready script

We see occasional name resolution failures on our tests slaves. Before
marking any of these nodes as ready in nodepool check that we can
resolve git.openstack.org and the local pypi mirror on that node.

This should help in preventing tests from failing with these errors by
catching them early and help in debugging by centralizing all occurences
of these failures in the nodepool logs.

Change-Id: I48ec87141687c1f6cd53eaada350fc5ce52cdef4

[{'created': '2014-06-04 15:25:14.000000000', 'message': "Add IPv6 management network support

This changeset adds support of IPv6 management network in devstack. Define
IP_MGMT_NET={ipv6 | ipv4} in your localrc to indicate if IPv6 or IPv4
management network shoule be used. Default management network is ipv4.

Note that there is a bug in eventlet that prevents the use of literal IPv6
addresses in URL. The fix to it hasn't been released. Therefore, it's
recommended that HOST_IP and SERVICE_HOST be explicitly defined with HOSTNAMES.

when literal IPv6 addresses are supported, make sure that HOST_IP and
SERVICE_HOST are using literal IPv6 address format when defining them in your
localrc. That is, quote the IPv6 address with '[' and ']'.

Also in your localrc, make sure to disable n-api-meta. There is a bug there
that prevents nova api from being started successfully.

Change-Id: Id913f8e25d75813de1c56abb63102b86f6dec0b5
Implements: blueprint ipv6-support
"}]
commit_message:
Add IPv6 management network support

This changeset adds support of IPv6 management network in devstack. Define
IP_MGMT_NET={ipv6 | ipv4} in your localrc to indicate if IPv6 or IPv4
management network shoule be used. Default management network is ipv4.

Note that there is a bug in eventlet that prevents the use of literal IPv6
addresses in URL. The fix to it hasn't been released. Therefore, it's
recommended that HOST_IP and SERVICE_HOST be explicitly defined with HOSTNAMES.

when literal IPv6 addresses are supported, make sure that HOST_IP and
SERVICE_HOST are using literal IPv6 address format when defining them in your
localrc. That is, quote the IPv6 address with '[' and ']'.

Also in your localrc, make sure to disable n-api-meta. There is a bug there
that prevents nova api from being started successfully.

Change-Id: Id913f8e25d75813de1c56abb63102b86f6dec0b5
Implements: blueprint ipv6-support

revisions:
[{'created': '2014-10-30 01:22:32.000000000', 'message': 'Update redis library to >=2.10.0

Tooz is using this library and is depending on a version that
has exceptions added in 2.10.0 so in order to avoid conflicts
we should bump up the redis to be at least that version. This
avoids mishaps later with other users that could be depending
on versions <2.10.0

Change-Id: Ia8e58f8cb6a19d2a12846a6a8f0e2e313d48f9a0
'}]
commit_message:
Update redis library to >=2.10.0

Tooz is using this library and is depending on a version that
has exceptions added in 2.10.0 so in order to avoid conflicts
we should bump up the redis to be at least that version. This
avoids mishaps later with other users that could be depending
on versions <2.10.0

Change-Id: Ia8e58f8cb6a19d2a12846a6a8f0e2e313d48f9a0

commit_message:
enforce requirements changes for barbican

barbican is an incubated project, but isn't in the requirements
sync job. This has allowed it to break the rest of the integrated
gate by pinning requirements that should not be allowed.

Enforce requirements on barbican and python-barbicanclient

Change-Id: If561857ef6eef8c5e4be7edc2caeb24bbe3805d8

'}, {'created': '2014-10-14 21:17:39.000000000', 'message': 'Change the stop operation for neutron-dhcp-agent.

1. Add the sending of term signal to dhcp process every 3 seconds
instead of one time, that should help to terminate the process faster.

2. Increase the time, which is left for cleaning up procedures.
In our configuration we have 60 seconds for stop operation:
40(was 55) seconds for stopping ONE neutron-dhcp-agent process and
20(was only 5) seconds for cleaning up ALL namespaces and processes in them.

commit_message:
Refactor the stop operation for neutron-dhcp-agent.

* Combine the stopping of neutron-dhcp-agent and the stopping of dnsmasq
processes inside namespaces into one time period (it was only for stopping of
ONE neutron dhcp process).
* Clean up duplicate code.

Change-Id: I71b8acc1da7171985854d08ad01a59d755d9d837
Closes-Bug: 1377906

we should try to use it if we are in that version (or newer) to

and call count and such).

Change-Id: I145e75327fa4f826fa0e93d3270952089da9784f
'}]
commit_message:
Use hdel with many keys where supported

Deletion of multiple keys in one call was added in 2.4.0 so
we should try to use it if we are in that version (or newer) to
avoid doing a loop that does the same (optimizing bandwidth
and call count and such).

Change-Id: I145e75327fa4f826fa0e93d3270952089da9784f

commit_message:
Ensure that we correctly expire (and cleanup) redis members

When a member has not heartbeated in a given amount of time
it should no longer be present in any of its associated groups,
to accomplish this we need to have a heartbeat key that each
member uses and have the group membership code fetch, check,
and clean members (if they are no longer alive).

Fixes bug 1386684

Change-Id: I89a8343ea9317c0522a6132ea065905b16b27b0d

Make requirement on redis 2.10.x explicit

The redis driver uses at least one class (TimeoutError) added
after 2.9.0.

commit_message:
Various fixes for locks and version compatibility

Avoid using lua locks

The default redis library will try to be smart about using
or not using lua based locks, it seems to not correctly predict
this correctly and then fails with errors such as:

''unknown command 'EVALSHA''

Upstream issue filed:

https://github.com/andymccurdy/redis-py/issues/550

The 'traditional' locks require PEXPIRE used by the redis-py
library which requires redis 2.6+ to actually work. So when
we are using a server version that is not new enough
we should conditionally raise a not implemented error to
avoid it later failing (which it will).

This also fixes a bunch of encoding issues that the enabling
of the py33 system now exposed (damn encodings...)

Change-Id: Ied6045276c9a1398db710a68aa75fe92aac9b4bb

commit_message:
Configure syslog listen UDP/514 for nodes

Load UDP module for Openstack nodes as well.
Required for Openstack Juno due to /dev/log
is not used for logging to syslog since
Juno (#1385295).

DocImpact
Closes-bug: #1381545

Change-Id: Ie9949574bef166e5d1b05921ee4bc9a6daec5137
Signed-off-by: Bogdan Dobrelya <bdobrelia@mirantis.com>

commit_message:
Raise an exception when quota config parameter is broken

Function get_remaining_quota returns None when quota config
param doesn't match a pattern (i.e. it's broken). It messes up 
the logic of its callers and leads to unpredictible behavior of 
the entire system.

This code raises InvalidOptionValue exception if config is broken

Change-Id: Ib08d2114f460d127aacf580fc519a58d6e8eba16

commit_message:
Add Fuel admin node IP to the list of environments

Usage:

    dos.py list --ips

Option '--ips' adds IP address of each Fuel admin node to
the list of environments.

Change-Id: I8298c7d295abc0657a74c4a155bd180ff7329701
