commit_message:
Make test_host_filters a NoDBTestCase

This is the final patch in the refactoring series. This changes the
test_host_filters.py file to contain just the test of the filter handler
system and cleans up the previously database-creating TestHostFilters
class.

The entire set of host filter unit tests (around 350 of them) now run in
less than 2 seconds, down from over a 45 seconds on my workstation.

Change-Id: I2f2518a08ac3f8c6addcd4055ee4c706c4c92e8e

[{'created': '2014-07-28 15:56:58.000000000', 'message': 'Move setup_instance_group to conductor

As part of the blueprint isolate-scheduler-db we identified that
there is a call from setup_instance_group to the Nova object
InstanceGroup. That prevents the scheduler to be split as a
separate project because it would have an external dependency to
a Nova object.
The implementation here is providing the call by the conductor
before the call to select_destinations as this method only
modifies filter_properties for adding group details.

Implements blueprint isolate-scheduler-db

Change-Id: Ib6556c8f6d6e6dcdb65a0bdb1894c66e92b35230
'}, {'created': '2014-08-08 15:43:29.000000000', 'message': 'Move setup_instance_group to conductor

As part of the blueprint isolate-scheduler-db we identified that
there is a call from setup_instance_group to the Nova object
InstanceGroup. That prevents the scheduler to be split as a
separate project because it would have an external dependency to
a Nova object.
The implementation here is providing the call by the conductor
before the call to select_destinations as this method only

commit_message:
Move setup_instance_group to conductor

During prework of scheduler split, we identified that
there is a call from setup_instance_group to the Nova object
InstanceGroup. That prevents the scheduler to be split as a
separate project because it would have an external dependency to
a Nova object.
The implementation here is providing the call by the conductor
before the call to select_destinations as this method only
modifies filter_properties for adding group details.

Co-Authored-By: Ed Leafe <ed@leafe.com>

Change-Id: Ib6556c8f6d6e6dcdb65a0bdb1894c66e92b35230

commit_message:
Fix public VIP gateway ping for neutron

We have different network scheme in astute.yaml for neutron. This
patch fixes public gateway calculation for pacemaker "ping"
resource when we use neutron.

Closes-bug: 1373375
Change-Id: Ia49ba52d3eab5dd5733450901e7a84a3448dbd3d

Hi, I just think compared to defining a very complicated name to identify different alarms, putting some customized info into description might be a better choice.'}, {'account_id': 6676, 'date': '2014-11-03 04:21:16.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

Alarm name is unique in each project, if you want to identify an alarm, its name is the best choice (besides the alarm_id). Unless you have some private implementation that using description for some other unusual usage, but that is not recommended.'}, {'account_id': 11034, 'date': '2014-11-03 05:20:59.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

Thanks for pointing this out. Actually we're now trying to handle the multi-region and multi-cloud scenario. We want to collect the alarms from different Openstack clouds which have their own ceilometer service. In this case, we hope alarms can bring more customized information to the alarm consumer to tell it who the alarm is and what really happened. But it seems the current alarm notification is insufficient for this. I guess a more generic solution is to add a metadata field which can be customized by user. But since the description field has similar functionality, we try to start from this. I agree that the name can also be a unique mark for alarm, but I'm not sure using it for this purpose is appropriate. Any suggestion for this? Thanks."}, {'account_id': 11034, 'date': '2014-11-03 08:57:11.000000000', 'content': 'Abandoned

Will use alarm name rather description to do this.'}]
revisions:
[{'created': '2014-11-03 00:43:59.000000000', 'message': 'Add description field to alarm notification

Currently, alarm notification only has the alarm_id which can be used
to identify an alarm. But in some use cases, user may want to use
some customized information to mark the alarm. So this patch added the
alarm description field into the notification. This field is defined
by users themself when the alarm is created and will be sent to the
alarm consumer(e.g. OS::Heat::ScalingPolicy) now.

commit_message:
Add description field to alarm notification

Currently, alarm notification only has the alarm_id which can be used
to identify an alarm. But in some use cases, user may want to use
some customized information to mark the alarm. So this patch added the
alarm description field into the notification. This field is defined
by users themself when the alarm is created and will be sent to the
alarm consumer(e.g. OS::Heat::ScalingPolicy) now.

Change-Id: Idd0e43fe79782658516e44a2df8a62611fb2d62a

commit_message:
Stop requiring os_region_name for glance providers

os_region_name may not be defined in glance.conf, so it should not be
required for glance commands. This patch will use the os_region_name
only if provided.

This is a fix for the problem introduced by
  https://review.openstack.org/#/c/125231/
and an alternative solution to
  https://review.openstack.org/#/c/130998/
that provides backward compatibility. It does not provide any path
forward for allowing configuration of os_region_name through a class
other than glance::backend::cinder.

This change breaks the tests, but I wanted to put this forward for
discussion before fixing the tests.

Change-Id: I23450382f2f4e09e01bc9312e3065f2372129c19

commit_message:
CDH Zookeeper Support

Sahara needs to support Zookeeper in CDH plugin. This proposal is
for a cdh cluster to support enabling Zookeeper service.

Blueprint: cdh-zookeeper-support

Thank you for your first contribution to OpenStack.

    Your patch will now be tested automatically by OpenStack testing frameworks
    and once the automatic tests pass, it will be reviewed by other friendly
    developers. They will give you feedback and may require you to refine it.

    People seldom get their patch approved on the first try, so don't be
    concerned if requested to make corrections. Feel free to modify your patch
    and resubmit a new change-set.

    Patches usually take 3 to 7 days to be reviewed so be patient and be
    available on IRC to ask and answer questions about your work. The more you
    participate in the community the more rewarding it is for you. You may also
    notice that the more you get to know people and get to be known, the faster
    your patches will be reviewed and eventually approved. Get to know others
    and become known by doing code reviews: anybody can do it, and it's a
    great way to learn the code base.

    Thanks again for supporting OpenStack, we look forward to working with you.

[{'created': '2014-11-01 18:14:04.000000000', 'message': "Disable python-barbicanclient 3.0.0 version

python-barbicanclient 3.0.0 has introduced cliff module, but pins it
to 1.6.1, while global-requirements set it to >=1.7.0, now the whole
OpenStack projects depends on higher version of cliff, but
python-barbicanclient is needed by cinder, then grenade test will
fail because: pkg_resources.DistributionNotFound: cliff==1.6.1

As long as python-barbicanclient maintainers don't provide a patch
for 3.0.0 (which seems not happen FMPOV), we need to disbable this
version.

Change-Id: Idd519fc3aa6e004aa75b56b36ffd125dde20f70e
Related-Bug: #1388414
"}]
commit_message:
Disable python-barbicanclient 3.0.0 version

python-barbicanclient 3.0.0 has introduced cliff module, but pins it
to 1.6.1, while global-requirements set it to >=1.7.0, now the whole
OpenStack projects depends on higher version of cliff, but
python-barbicanclient is needed by cinder, then grenade test will
fail because: pkg_resources.DistributionNotFound: cliff==1.6.1

As long as python-barbicanclient maintainers don't provide a patch
for 3.0.0 (which seems not happen FMPOV), we need to disbable this
version.

Change-Id: Idd519fc3aa6e004aa75b56b36ffd125dde20f70e
Related-Bug: #1388414

commit_message:
Typo in "Tutorial: Building a Dashboard using Horizon"

In the tutorial "Building a Dashboard using Horizon" there is a bug
in the view.py example that in case of exception return a var that
has not been defined.

Closes-Bug: #1388576

commit_message:
Make sure that tox uses python2 by default

Our documentation tools are not python3 compatible, so make sure that
tox creates python2 virtual environments during tests.

Thank you for your first contribution to OpenStack.

    Your patch will now be tested automatically by OpenStack testing frameworks
    and once the automatic tests pass, it will be reviewed by other friendly
    developers. They will give you feedback and may require you to refine it.

    People seldom get their patch approved on the first try, so don't be
    concerned if requested to make corrections. Feel free to modify your patch
    and resubmit a new change-set.

    Patches usually take 3 to 7 days to be reviewed so be patient and be
    available on IRC to ask and answer questions about your work. The more you
    participate in the community the more rewarding it is for you. You may also
    notice that the more you get to know people and get to be known, the faster
    your patches will be reviewed and eventually approved. Get to know others
    and become known by doing code reviews: anybody can do it, and it's a
    great way to learn the code base.

    Thanks again for supporting OpenStack, we look forward to working with you.

commit_message:
roles/admin.pp: Allow one to specify various $admin_roles

Currently, there is no way to specify various admin roles, just 'admin'.
This PR aims to make this behavior more flexible.

Change-Id: I3acba631008b736c7d2d383b86ee97560b589512

commit_message:
Allow for any order of user_roles

Change insync determination of the roles list to be order
agnostic.  The specific order in which the user roles
appear in keystone does not matter.

Closes-Bug: 1372493

Change-Id: Iaee28f45ebb68acbe3ed70e7c45d9397140169f3

commit_message:
add config for caching metadata in memory

* add config metadata_memory_cache_ttl to enable caching metadata
in memory
* set default to 5 as project neutron/master

Change-Id: Ib6a05ae5033c53c4196f736373752370012d82a6

commit_message:
Fix s3_token filter configuration for swift-proxy

Since Juno s3_token middleware is a part of keystoneclient, not
keystone.

Closes-bug: 1384149

The nova_admin_tenant_id_setter class internally generates a
neutron_config resource that isn't collected by the normal
Neutron_Config collector.  This means we need an explicit dependency
between the neutron package and any nova_admin_tenant_id_setter
resources, to ensure that the config files exist.

Change-Id: I713bd6a9cc496947f10faa3ccc67f8362c872839
"}]
commit_message:
Neutron dep for nova_admin_tenant_id_setter

The nova_admin_tenant_id_setter class internally generates a
neutron_config resource that isn't collected by the normal
Neutron_Config collector.  This means we need an explicit dependency
between the neutron package and any nova_admin_tenant_id_setter
resources, to ensure that the config files exist.

Change-Id: I713bd6a9cc496947f10faa3ccc67f8362c872839

revisions:
[{'created': '2014-10-23 23:01:01.000000000', 'message': "Fix db sync relationships

- The trove module does not specify a 'trove' package resource, so use
  the 'python-troveclient' package resource.
- The trove module does not specify a 'DEFAULT/sql_connection'
  keystone_config resource and has no need to manage keystone configs,
  so use trove_config.
- The trove module does not specify a 'trove' user. The trove user is
  created by the trove client package, which is already related by the
  subscribe metaparameter, so remove the require relationship.

Change-Id: I4e9ae0403439a51889e5fb884e689f91b874ad4d
"}]
commit_message:
Fix db sync relationships

- The trove module does not specify a 'trove' package resource, so use
  the 'python-troveclient' package resource.
- The trove module does not specify a 'DEFAULT/sql_connection'
  keystone_config resource and has no need to manage keystone configs,
  so use trove_config.
- The trove module does not specify a 'trove' user. The trove user is
  created by the trove client package, which is already related by the
  subscribe metaparameter, so remove the require relationship.

Change-Id: I4e9ae0403439a51889e5fb884e689f91b874ad4d

commit_message:
Add parameter to set os_region_name in glance config

When https://review.openstack.org/#/c/125231/ was merged, the glance
providers became dependent on the DEFAULT/os_region_name parameter in
the glance configs, but the module had no way to set that parameter.
This caused the providers to fail.

This patch adds the parameter to glance::api so that the user can
control the value. It also removes functionality of the os_region_name
in glance::backend::cinder. While it would be better to deprecate this
parameter first and remove its functionality in a later release, there
is no clean way to do this and avoid a duplicate definition error.

An alternative to rapidly removing this functionality from
glance::backend::cinder would be modifying the glance parent provider
to make the DEFAULT/os_region_name glance config optional.

Change-Id: I075224acb9da2bb547d437b08cf6fccfed655d5c

commit_message:
Fixed a bug in multi level restore and added new --action arg

- Fixed an issue when restoring multi level backup with queues
- Added th new option --action {backup, restore, info, admin}
- Extended examples in README and other minors log msg changes
- Changed homepage to github in setup.py

Change-Id: I5fa13971a3134d7f001dc3ce5aeabbc95a10626a

In some cases negative values can be returned for resources currently
in use. When this occurs, the project overview page fails with an
error 500 due to an OverflowError, "cannot convert float infinity to
integer". Handle this case more gracefully.

Change-Id: Id1ad16eafdde906dc74bfafc7f72ea8d3bdcdc8f
Closes-Bug: #1386687
(cherry picked from commit 53c7dc022ed4e0d5d60fb344b3e8c94e3dfb7d43)
'}]
commit_message:
Handle negative values in total*Used for Cinder absolute limits

In some cases negative values can be returned for resources currently
in use. When this occurs, the project overview page fails with an
error 500 due to an OverflowError, "cannot convert float infinity to
integer". Handle this case more gracefully.

Change-Id: Id1ad16eafdde906dc74bfafc7f72ea8d3bdcdc8f
Closes-Bug: #1386687
(cherry picked from commit 53c7dc022ed4e0d5d60fb344b3e8c94e3dfb7d43)

Thank you for your first contribution to OpenStack.

    Your patch will now be tested automatically by OpenStack testing frameworks
    and once the automatic tests pass, it will be reviewed by other friendly
    developers. They will give you feedback and may require you to refine it.

    People seldom get their patch approved on the first try, so don't be
    concerned if requested to make corrections. Feel free to modify your patch
    and resubmit a new change-set.

    Patches usually take 3 to 7 days to be reviewed so be patient and be
    available on IRC to ask and answer questions about your work. The more you
    participate in the community the more rewarding it is for you. You may also
    notice that the more you get to know people and get to be known, the faster
    your patches will be reviewed and eventually approved. Get to know others
    and become known by doing code reviews: anybody can do it, and it's a
    great way to learn the code base.

    Thanks again for supporting OpenStack, we look forward to working with you.

    IRC: https://wiki.openstack.org/wiki/IRC
    Workflow: https://wiki.openstack.org/wiki/Gerrit_Workflow
    Commit Messages: https://wiki.openstack.org/wiki/GitCommitMessages"}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2014-11-01 16:30:58.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Verified+1

commit_message:
Don't include the not-yet-written HOT sections

Instead of displaying a bunch of TODOs, comment out the sections that
need to be written to provide a cleaner output.

The intent is to have a first release of the HOT guide in the user
guide.

Change-Id: I116e5c1cee1922b19cc80a2e09c261ee38a180e9

commit_message:
Manually fix a wrong default in the config ref

Add the missing /v2 at the end of the neutron nova_url option.

The tools and dependencies brought by pip have changed since the
Icehouse release so running autohelp.py generates a lot of changes that
we don't want to see happening.

Change-Id: Ibac14689f0ba855efb00008ecd74657641a365ce
Closes-Bug: #1338613

    Your patch will now be tested automatically by OpenStack testing frameworks

    People seldom get their patch approved on the first try, so don't be

commit_message:
Added doc for trove clustering

The trove chapter in the user guide did not have
a section on how to set up database clustering.

This commit covers how to create a sharded
MongoDB cluster.

Change-Id: I9438272b0b5a9d48ef56e6c5447df66b1b8e371f
Closes-Bug: #1386849

commit_message:
Brick LVM: Rename get_all_volumes, further optimize

This method can process all LVs, those in a VG, or an
individual LV.  Rename it to be more descriptive.

Optimize update_volume_group_info check for thin pool.

Remove volume.utils.get_all_volumes, which is unused.

Remove fake_lvm.get_all_volumes and
fake_lvm.get_all_volume_groups which don't appear to
have correct signatures/returns and are unused.

Change-Id: I412c62230517cbfc08cc0076aaeea45224e6b50e

commit_message:
Nova consoleauth service fails in HA configuration

Nova consoleauth is a singleton service. In an HA configuration currently
it runs on all the controllers and causes NoVNC to fail intermittently
when it tries to connect to the URL that the API returned to it.

This fix makes consoleauth only run on the bootstrap node.

Change-Id: Ic1803e0b997271b3512e6c62fd75feccb4d9be0a

commit_message:
Fixed issue with max size for Swift objects

Fixed issue with max size of object, which Glance
should store in Swift without slicing.
Default value doesn't work when user attempts to make
a snapshots with size > 300 Mb.

Change-Id: Ic3b3120605f1e1536a34bedc4ad5c0c2f4c8510b
Closes-Bug: #1373813

commit_message:
Change location of [glance_store] options

I moved the [glance_store] configuration options from the
glance-registry.conf file to the glance-api.conf file. I
also fixed a minor wording consistency with the optional
step to enable verbose logging.

Change-Id: I730dacc91ceb9fc1b689796dc19f2e79e5b91276
Closes-Bug: #1388379
backport: juno
(cherry picked from commit 829bf95b9fadf25394f41377df4a7ebce471bc74)

Thank you for your first contribution to OpenStack.

    Your patch will now be tested automatically by OpenStack testing frameworks
    and once the automatic tests pass, it will be reviewed by other friendly
    developers. They will give you feedback and may require you to refine it.

    People seldom get their patch approved on the first try, so don't be
    concerned if requested to make corrections. Feel free to modify your patch
    and resubmit a new change-set.

    Patches usually take 3 to 7 days to be reviewed so be patient and be
    available on IRC to ask and answer questions about your work. The more you
    participate in the community the more rewarding it is for you. You may also
    notice that the more you get to know people and get to be known, the faster
    your patches will be reviewed and eventually approved. Get to know others
    and become known by doing code reviews: anybody can do it, and it's a
    great way to learn the code base.

    Thanks again for supporting OpenStack, we look forward to working with you.

    IRC: https://wiki.openstack.org/wiki/IRC
    Workflow: https://wiki.openstack.org/wiki/Gerrit_Workflow
    Commit Messages: https://wiki.openstack.org/wiki/GitCommitMessages"}, {'account_id': 13823, 'date': '2014-11-01 16:14:46.000000000', 'content': 'Abandoned

That was just a test from the upstream training'}]

commit_message:
Keep migration status if instance still resizing

There is a race condition during finish_resize() where
poll_unconfirmed_resizes() can get called between the database save
of the migration record and instance record. The migration record
will be marked 'finished', enabling poll_unconfirmed_resizes() to pick
it up. But the instance will not have been saved yet to have the
vm_state of RESIZED, and task_state of None. The task_state will
still be RESIZE_FINISH. This will cause poll_unconfirmed_resizes() to
put the migration record in error state.

Instead, poll_unconfirmed_resizes() should ignore instances with
a task state of RESIZE_FINISH and not put the migration record
into error state.

Change-Id: I825234de5e4a4f0cc906ac05b715ed85cd953aa1
Closes-Bug: #1376933
(cherry picked from commit 0a84bb80c2ea66a806395964684e07d7bc6accbd)

commit_message:
Change location of [glance_store] options

I moved the [glance_store] configuration options from the
glance-registry.conf file to the glance-api.conf file. I
also fixed a minor wording consistency with the optional
step to enable verbose logging.

Change-Id: I730dacc91ceb9fc1b689796dc19f2e79e5b91276
Closes-Bug: #1388379
backport: juno

commit_message:
Do not log when reraising an exception

It should be up to the caller to use the log level error
when the exception is reraised. For example, if the call
to a VIM api fails, _poll_task is currently throwing a big
red block even if the caller ignores the exception.

This patch removes the logging from _poll_task.

Change-Id: I5bceb41c9a24dca45ff8689daee0eeafa7da839c

commit_message:
Always manage local_settings.py

If $compress_offline is false, local_settings.py becomes unmanaged
by Puppet. This is clearly wrong.

Move local_settings.py file resource out of condition and
establish notification relationship conditionally to $compress_offline
instead.

Closes-bug: #1383473
Change-Id: Ia7e4bc8e8f74c62ac624056883fb8c2910e2fe09

commit_message:
Add dhcp-sequential-ip option to dnsmasq

For many simultaneously DHCPDISCOVER requests dnsmasq
can offer the same IP for two different MAC addresses.
This option prevents it by assigning IPs one by one
instead of using hashing algorithm.

Change-Id: Iff3c42d21e1f1c09cb9eab5f07dbb066508dcb56
Related-bug: 1378000
Related-bug: 1376680
Related-bug: 1379917
Blueprint: 100-nodes-support

commit_message:
Fix default Apache config cleanup on Ubuntu

The configuration file /etc/apache2/conf.d/openstack-dashboard.conf
is not properly cleaned on Ubuntu platforms.

The configuration file is actually a symbolic link and
it looks like Puppet cannot manage its content if ensure
is present is used on the file resource.

This bug manifests itself with Puppet <= 3.2.x:
https://projects.puppetlabs.com/issues/6808

Updating the actual file on Ubuntu platforms fixes the problem.

Closes-bug: #1382222
Change-Id: I673d991f0de4d899cffc07a8ec6d60dbc4a1fb39

Currently cinder eqlx_san_thin_provision option is false to
disable creation of thin-provisioned volumes.
The default should be true to enable thin provisioning which is the recommended setting.

There is a Openstack launchpad bug to fix documentation:
https://bugs.launchpad.net/openstack-manuals/+bug/1384927

Change-Id: I4252da3e60004998c3cd15921ac403bd8969ee57
'}]
commit_message:
Default setting san_thin_provision should be true

Currently cinder eqlx_san_thin_provision option is false to
disable creation of thin-provisioned volumes.
The default should be true to enable thin provisioning which is the recommended setting.

There is a Openstack launchpad bug to fix documentation:
https://bugs.launchpad.net/openstack-manuals/+bug/1384927

Change-Id: I4252da3e60004998c3cd15921ac403bd8969ee57

commit_message:
Allow multiple networks to be created per cluster

Added a NodeGroup model. NodeGroups can be created and modified
via the Fuel API. Clusters are created with a default node group
and the cluster networks are tied to that default node group.

Upon creation of a node group a set of networks will be generated.
When a node group is deleted those networks will be deleted as well.

See previous change: Ic30a1b46112599022645b06f7bef2223ff4c6475

DocImpact
Change-Id: I8bbe6b8c6338d6586c7e9a61542939ae2a19828b
Implements: blueprint multiple-cluster-networks

[{'created': '2014-04-14 22:34:35.000000000', 'message': 'Multiple Cluster Networks: add ip rule route

Adds support for ip route rules (ip route policy) to interfaces
 with gateways supplied. This will create a policy based default
 route for said interface. This is necessary to provide return
 routes when multiple cluster networks are defined, otherwise
 packets would only return on the default interface when the are
 outside of the network of the interface.

Adds disabled code to configure haproxy to keep vip points together
 There are some deployment cases where the deployer may need to
 enable this and this serves as the code example to perform it.

Resolves-bug #1272766
implments: bp multiple-cluster-networks

'}, {'created': '2014-10-13 21:05:10.000000000', 'message': "Multiple Cluster Networks: IP routes

Adds new attributes 'is_default_route' and 'other_nets' to
 l23network::l3::ifconfig.

In multiple cluster networks it is necessary for interfaces each have their
 own gateway. This adds 'is_default_route' so that only one interface will
 receive the default gateway route. This is assured by nailgun.

It is also necessary for each interface to know the route to the other
 networks of the same network role from other NodeGroups in the cluster. These
 networks are expressed in 'other_nets' and with the 'gateway' and interface
 name will be used to add routes to the node

data used from asute.yaml

Neutron network provider:
network_scheme:
  endpoints:
...
    br-fw-admin:
      IP:
      - 10.108.47.3/24
      default_gateway: true
      gateway: 10.108.47.1
      other_nets:
      - 10.108.52.0/24
    br-mgmt:
      IP:
      - 10.108.49.2/24
      gateway: 10.108.49.1
      other_nets:
      - 10.108.54.0/24
...

Nova network provider:
network_data:
...
  eth1:
    default_gateway: true
    gateway: 10.108.48.1
    interface: eth1
    ipaddr:
    - 10.108.48.4/24
...

Adds disabled code to configure haproxy to keep vip points together
 There are some deployment cases where the deployer may need to
 enable this and this serves as the code example to perform it.

Resolves-bug #1272766
implments: bp multiple-cluster-networks

Change-Id: I06e09fd9b292cac53b925933006de064e725bdb0

commit_message:
Multiple Cluster Networks: IP routes

Adds new attributes 'is_default_route' and 'other_nets' to
 l23network::l3::ifconfig.

Adds ability for ns_IPaddr2 to consume other_nets

In multiple cluster networks it is necessary for interfaces each have their
 own gateway. This adds 'is_default_route' so that only one interface will
 receive the default gateway route. This is assured by nailgun.

It is also necessary for each interface to know the route to the other
 networks of the same network role from other NodeGroups in the cluster. These
 networks are expressed in 'other_nets' and with the 'gateway' and interface
 name will be used to add routes to the node

data used from asute.yaml

Neutron network provider:
network_scheme:
  endpoints:
...
    br-fw-admin:
      IP:
      - 10.108.47.3/24
      default_gateway: true
      gateway: 10.108.47.1
      other_nets:
      - 10.108.52.0/24
    br-mgmt:
      IP:
      - 10.108.49.2/24
      gateway: 10.108.49.1
      other_nets:
      - 10.108.54.0/24
...

Nova network provider:
network_data:
...
  eth1:
    default_gateway: true
    gateway: 10.108.48.1
    interface: eth1
    ipaddr:
    - 10.108.48.4/24
...

Adds disabled code to configure haproxy to keep vip points together
 There are some deployment cases where the deployer may need to
 enable this and this serves as the code example to perform it.

Resolves-bug #1272766
implments: blueprint multiple-cluster-networks

Change-Id: I06e09fd9b292cac53b925933006de064e725bdb0

commit_message:
Set default gateway to admin network gateway for provisioning

The default gateway will be set to the gateway provided in ks_meta
by nailgun. This is required to support cases where a node's admin
network is not the same subnet as the master node.

Change-Id: I1e689776264aa8e56ca25efd074902c0a31dc235

commit_message:
host manager: Log the host generating the warning

Currently we are logging a warning when there's a discrepancy between
the host's available disk stored in the database and the disk reported
by the compute node, but there's no information about which host
generates that error.

Change-Id: I8d6704fa76f2750e0e986b8399f9fe358b3fad93

commit_message:
Fix reference to puppet-pull for syncing the nodes

The documentation refers to a puppet-run instead of puppet-pull command
because of a misprint.

The puppet-pull script was introduced into fuel-library with:
https://review.openstack.org/#/c/63950/

Closes-Bug: 1364886
Change-Id: I546550e7858d1d03de0931ff777802e5b141fd04

commit_message:
Run build_and_run_instance in a separate greenthread

If we're doing a lot of build operations, we are using a large portion
of the limited rpc worker pool for long periods of time. Since we may wait
on external services (like neutron or glance) during those times, we could
fully deplete that pool.

This patch makes us spawn a new greenthread for that task and return the
rpc worker to the pool. Due to some funkiness with the stack of decorators,
this breaks the inner function out to an object method, which is probably
good anyway, given its size. This also moves the wrap_instance_event
decorator to the inner function so that the start and stop events properly
demarcate the actual task and not just the (now very quick) RPC call.

Change-Id: Ife712c43c5a61424bc68b2f5ab47cefdb46ac168
Closes-Bug: #1372049

commit_message:
Create un-used params to pass tests for multiple-cluster-networks

https://review.openstack.org/#/c/99179/

The nailgun changes in 99179 create two new attribues in the network
 yaml scheme. other_nets and default_gateway. In the advanced_networks
 provider it sends all of the data to l23netowk::l3::ifconfig. This commit
 will create these values so that the tests can pass for the nailgun changes.

https://review.openstack.org/#/c/87400/

After the nailgun changes are merged then 87400 will be able to pass CI

partially-implments blueprint multiple-cluster-networks

Change-Id: I7e6a6ff2cb6b43276256805bab96a54570f40f6b

commit_message:
Record and retrieve table creation timestamp

Extend the magnetodb.table_info table with an additional
"creation_date_time" column to store the creation timestamp of each table.
Return the creation timestamp in relevant REST API calls.

For consistency, renamed the last_updated column to last_update_time_date.

Closes-Bug: #1298814

Change-Id: I02b920b866529027655802c4d880f7557329824a

commit_message:
Drop and recreate FK if adding new PK to routerl3bindings

Since MySQL 5.6 FK columns cannot be altered. As a workaround we can
drop the FK before ALTER COLUMN and then recreate it.

Change-Id: I069be948b07c894c2c340e1192515be25a59d6e1
Closes-Bug: 1384555

commit_message:
VMware: Add fake.create_vm()

Add a utility function for creating VMs in tests. Based on the
existing FakeVim._create_vm function which implements CreateVM_Task.
FakeVim._create_vm is refactored to call create_vm.

Change-Id: I4949408420704cd7e6dd4fc11226472362422a93

def set_vif_bandwidth_config(conf, inst_type):
    """Config vif inbound/outbound bandwidth limit. parameters are
    set in instance_type_extra_specs table, key is in  the format
    quota:vif_inbound_average.
    """

    bandwidth_items = ['vif_inbound_average', 'vif_inbound_peak',
        'vif_inbound_burst', 'vif_outbound_average', 'vif_outbound_peak',
        'vif_outbound_burst']
    for key, value in inst_type.get('extra_specs', {}).iteritems():
        scope = key.split(':')
        if len(scope) > 1 and scope[0] == 'quota':
            if scope[1] in bandwidth_items:

commit_message:
Read flavor even if it is already deleted

Currently libvirt code has some references to Flavor
as objects.Flavor.get_by_id. because the flavor might be
deleted before it's referenced, so most code need to
read deleted flavor in libvirt driver. This patch
makes the _prepare_args_for_get_config which is used for
sriov feature consistent to other Flavor get functions.

Related-Bug: #1352668

Change-Id: Ia4a03467720f1fed18cabe1b78bdd4488f316e34

commit_message:
Make nondeterministic tests more robust

Previously, we were testing the nondeterministic message
bus DSE by publishing messages and sleeping for a second
before proceeding with the test.  On slow machines, a second
was not always enough time and produced failures in Jenkins.

This change uses the 'retrying' package to wait until
a condition becomes true.  And because dse now uses
eventlet we can safely reduce the time we wait to
much less than a second, thereby signficantly reducing
the time we wait.

Closes-bug: 1381917
Closes-bug: 1381044
Closes-bug: 1381043
Change-Id: I2812351537cd330bd198c122d9804302781a10d3

This document is mainly designed to give a high level overview of the project to others, non-developers, managers, Foundation's staff and board. 

The main objective of this review is to have PTLs and the TC look at the numbers shown in each project especially and give their opinion on the validity. Please focus on the hard facts shown and we can discuss separately how to improve the report for the next quarter, which other numbers to extrapolate. 

Minor nit: I think the latex/ subdir is not needed. There should also be a README to explain how to build the dvi/pdf out of latex. We're going to add it. You should be able to checkout the patch and build it though.

Another known issue: lots of trailing spaces, please ignore them :) Look at the charts, they're pretty :)"}, {'account_id': 2284, 'date': '2014-10-29 21:39:32.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2:

How about adding a doc build job to the CI for this repo, so that the generated and easily consumable can be browsed in the  build results, as opposed to requiring reviewers to build the latex source?

(as would currently be the case for say patches proposed to the docbook source in openstack-manuals).

Just a thought.

Cheers,
Eoghan'}, {'account_id': 287, 'date': '2014-10-29 21:47:41.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2:

For the future we can think of something like that. At the moment, the best option is that we upload the PDF with the patch. Would that be better for this iteration?'}, {'account_id': 4257, 'date': '2014-10-30 01:53:12.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2:

I think I see the methodology in there, but can you confirm that the date range for this data is July-September? I'm mildly curious just because the first readable thing I found to compare to a different source was wildly off (by a factor of 1.5 or more in both directions):

https://review.openstack.org/#/c/131854/2/reports/2014-q3/latex/data/scm_top_authors_project_heat.csv
https://github.com/openstack/heat/graphs/contributors?from=2014-07-01&to=2014-09-30&type=c

I'm not suggesting the numbers can't be justified - if a commit is authored by one person, committed by another person and submitted for review by a third person, who should get credit? (afaict it's the third person in this case) - but I was surprised by the size of the discrepancy.

Also, 3 months seems an odd timeframe to be doing comparisons between, since you'll be comparing the end of a development cycle to the beginning of one... a rolling 6-month window would seem to make more sense?

+1 for including the PDF in the patch for now."}, {'account_id': 8000, 'date': '2014-10-30 12:45:30.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 3.'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2014-10-30 12:45:32.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3: Verified+1

- noop http://logs.openstack.org/54/131854/3/check/noop/a6739c7 : SUCCESS'}, {'account_id': 8000, 'date': '2014-10-30 12:46:54.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3:

New patch version with the pdf file as suggested and a readme in the root directory.'}, {'account_id': 8000, 'date': '2014-10-30 13:17:35.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3:

Zane, the period of analysis goes from the first of July till the 30th of September, both dates included. In other words: third quarter of 2014.

You'll see across the document that all of the charts show the last 8 quarters.

Regarding to your specific comments, the owner of the commit is the one who authored it. Git is the one providing such information so the initial author of the commit (registered in Git or in a sent patch) should be the author of it. We also made a small analysis about people co-authoring those commits (specified in the commit log). However the number of those commits was pretty low if compared to the general activity of the community, so this was left as further work.

Then, regarding to the comparison with GitHub, there are some differences in the methodology. For instance, GitHub specifies that those charts are only for master (we aggregate all branches), commits in forks do not appear and so on. However, given that this is a mirror, I'm not sure how GitHub really behaves with this type of repositories. Some more info about what GitHub analyzes and understand as a commit at [1].

From the activity board side, we analyze any branch, so extra commits may appear if compared to GitHub. Basically we trust a lot on 'git log' command (with some options). As a quick example if I run a basic command line script [2] to check this, and for instance, for Steve Baker I get around 57 commits, while GitHub provides 39 for such period (the csv file provides 59, which is quite a similar number). For you, this number is of 26, similar to the 27 provided in the csv file.

So, concluding :), my perception is that this is a matter of methodology. I'm not defending this approach against others, although we should probably fully understand and agree how to measure these metrics. This is a possibility among others :).

I hope this clarifies a bit the process. In any case, at the end of the pdf file there's a list of analyzed URLs and definitions that can keep improving.

[1] https://help.github.com/articles/why-are-my-contributions-not-showing-up-on-my-profile/
[2] git log --since 2014/07/01 --until 2014/09/30 | grep ^Author | sort | grep "Steve Baker" |  wc -l'}, {'account_id': 8000, 'date': '2014-10-30 16:41:35.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 4.'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2014-10-30 16:41:38.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 4: Verified+1

This patchset fixes the reported error for the Documentation project. Please, check that this is fixed. The error was related to the number of tickets detected as closed. In the case of the Documentation project, the Fix Released status was not considered.

This patchset also updates the pdf file.'}, {'account_id': 287, 'date': '2014-10-31 20:59:47.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 4: Code-Review+2 Workflow+1

One thing I'd like to add is that more than the individual numbers, trends are more the points of this analysis. Analyzing the same dataset over time and calculated indexes should give us a better understanding of the dynamics of the whole project.

commit_message:
This report is produced quarterly to give Community Managers
and OpenStack Foundation's management better insights on development
activities and online conversations. The quantitative and qualitative
assessment start from tracking actions across all OpenStack git
repositories, gerrit code reviews, bug trackers as well as IRC channels,
mailing lists and questions/answers.

This is the second issue of the report.

Change-Id: I89ca4da22f59da465738326f143e1224cb96a674

The v3 client was written assuming that some arguments
would be renamed for better consistency.   V2.1 will follow
the v2 syntax,  so we need to convert the client back to
that.

This change converts os-scheduler-hints:scheduler-hints in the
server element to os:scheduler-hints in the main body

Change-Id: Ib4f98daa230b0626dd720cd36baf4d3f34e0c524
'}]
commit_message:
novaclient: Convert v3 boot command with v2.1 spec (scheduler-hints)

The v3 client was written assuming that some arguments
would be renamed for better consistency.   V2.1 will follow
the v2 syntax,  so we need to convert the client back to
that.

This change converts os-scheduler-hints:scheduler-hints in the
server element to os:scheduler-hints in the main body

Change-Id: Ib4f98daa230b0626dd720cd36baf4d3f34e0c524

commit_message:
novaclient: Convert v3 boot command with v2.1 spec (flavorRef)

The v3 client was written assuming that some arguments
would be renamed for better consistency.  Currently the V3
client is the only way we have to test the V2.1 API, which
will follow the v2 syntax,  so we need to convert the v3 clients
back to V2.1 syntac until teh APi is fully V2 compatible.

This change converts flavor_ref to flavorRef

Change-Id: Ia5b154fb7796c0d497e80e7b312f58500f38a506

The original bug is for missing attribute type definition. I agree with Dima to have the check in parser and throw appropriate message such as "missing attribute type".'}, {'account_id': 8491, 'date': '2014-10-31 14:21:34.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2:

@Charles: In fact i DO believe that AttributeType constructor is the place for this validation. We allow only very limited set of inputs for the constructor and validate that input to be in set. And please note that we call that constructor during attribute type parsing as well, so we do that validation in parser.
Actually I talked with Dima and he agreed with me.

And please note tempest/api/keyvalue/stable/rest/test_create_table_negative.py. I added test case exactly for the bug -- missing attribute type.'}, {'account_id': 8491, 'date': '2014-10-31 14:23:34.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 3.'}, {'account_id': 8491, 'date': '2014-10-31 14:28:49.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 4.'}, {'account_id': 11006, 'date': '2014-10-31 14:36:00.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 4:

I suggest to call out "missing attribute type" as a separate validation error unless you have a strong opinion against it.'}, {'account_id': 8491, 'date': '2014-10-31 14:46:47.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 4:

@Charles: To have exactly that error message ('missing attribute type') we need to have separate validation. But I don't see real difference between missing attr type or 'None' attr type and, say 123 as attr type. For all that cases we have checks in AttributeType constructor.

commit_message:
Add wsgi_chunked_request option

This option is necessary[1] when running OpenStack's keystone on Apache.
This functionality has been merged[2] into the upstream puppetlabs-apache.

[1] https://review.openstack.org/#/c/34835/
[2] https://github.com/puppetlabs/puppetlabs-apache/pull/890

Conflicts:
	manifests/wsgi/apache.pp
	spec/classes/keystone_wsgi_apache_spec.rb

Change-Id: Ifa2cc3907252e2bafd9248a695e81f4d9444d243

commit_message:
Do not call configure several times at startup

At startup, Glance first creates the stores and then verifies
the default store. Each of these operations will indirectly
trigger the creation of store objects which is triggering configure
and configure_add calls.
configure and configure_add can potentially contain remote calls
going through the network: we should avoid having these methods
called two times for nothing.

This patch adds a parameter in the store init method to specify
if the configuration of the store should happen. In case of verify
default store, the configuration should not happen.

Closes-Bug: #1315237

Change-Id: I329730a3351cd7b78de27a88a7f669ae32b2f100
(cherry-picked from commit c9a034c838e2c5a1f636656ead9aa3b6f7d06603)

commit_message:
Do not kill dnsmasq instances started by init.

When specifying a specific DNS server in /etc/network/interfaces:

auto eth0
iface eth0 inet dhcp
    dns-nameservers 8.8.8.8

and having the same dns-server specified in /etc/dhcp/dhclient.conf:

prepend domain-name-servers 8.8.8.8;

and restarting the machine will make stack.sh to fail because the
dnsmasq created by init is deleted, consequently, it won't be possible
to download the cirros image.

With this patch, stack.sh won't kill dnsmasq instances sarted by
/sbin/init (pid 1).

Change-Id: I2a6dad0dbc99246ed9bd96f85ffeeecb94d8f846
Closes-Bug: #1341885

subject: Adding skip if service disabled based on Tempest config

commit_message:
Initiate deletion of image files if the import was interrupted

If the image is deleted by appropriate API call while its content
is still being uploaded in import task in v2, an exception is raised
and it is not handled in the API code. This leads to the fact that
the uploaded image file stays in a storage and clogs it.

There existed code that safely removes image files if the exception
occurs.

Change-Id: I4f7d1aa103f4ce7abf4026e7097b9e76c24135fa
Closes-Bug: 1371118

commit_message:
Use sizelimit from oslo.middleware

Module sizelimit in nova and oslo.middleware is the same, so
switch nova to use RequestBodySizalimiter from oslo.middleware
lib

Replace RequestBodySizalimiter and LimitingReader by temporal
aliases of this classes in oslo.middleware due to failures in grenade

commit_message:
Convert files to use _LE and friends

LOG.warn etc. should be translated separately and thus messages need to
be marked with _LW for LOG.warn, _LI for LOG.info and _LE for LOG.errors
and LOG.exception.

Mark all LOG invocations with proper translation marker.

Use ',' instead of '%' when adding variables to log messages to allow
lazy evaluation.

Add new hacking checks for these.

Change-Id: I31d3ee50f30c63d7d647b1c2b1eae50bf96f0c74

commit_message:
Fix context storage bug

Fix a bug with storing the request context in thread local where the
storage was not properly cleared between requests.

(This was causing the same request to always be logged.)

Closes-Bug: 1384911
Change-Id: Ie30b93900451b0f9f6fd8158457b0b66903af470

[{'created': '2014-10-30 15:26:26.000000000', 'message': "Couchbase backup failing

Executing a backup on Couchbase doesn't finish. Examining the log in
the Guest Agent revealed the following error:
'OSError: [Errno 2] No such file or directory'

This occurred because a list was being passed to 'execute' instead of
*args. These instances have been fixed.

Change-Id: I4616437909a31818faf082f0c272de9415219acd
Closes-Bug: #1387721
"}]
commit_message:
Couchbase backup failing

Executing a backup on Couchbase doesn't finish. Examining the log in
the Guest Agent revealed the following error:
'OSError: [Errno 2] No such file or directory'

This occurred because a list was being passed to 'execute' instead of
*args. These instances have been fixed.

Change-Id: I4616437909a31818faf082f0c272de9415219acd

commit_message:
Add a gate job for zaqar-redis

A new redis drier was recently added to Zaqar. The team would like to
have a test job that checks *all* patches against this driver as well.

This patch adds such job to the infrastructure configs. It's based on
the already existing job but it enables redis by setting `ZAQAR_BACKEND`
in the gate environment.

The patch adds jobs for Zaqar, tempest experimental and devstack
experimental.

This patch depends on: I97629a303c55ee098e3bfbc534bfb05ccab94649

Change-Id: Icb260f27e01d024fe98cf03f68a7285ec4bb3b71

commit_message:
fixing the iSER transport protocol when using LVMISERDriver

ISER capabilities were broken in icehouse when trying to remove
duplication between ISCSIDriver and ISERDriver.

This fix does minimal changes in the code in order to fix
the capability.

The fix is basically re-adding the ISERTgtAdm and re-adding
the support in LVMISERDriver: change target_lun based on
iseradm.

Conflicts:
        cinder/volume/driver.py

Changes from the original fix in Juno:

Bug https://bugs.launchpad.net/cinder/+bug/1325799
caused the volumes to be created with iSCSI's prefix
parameter in any case. In order to solve the prefix mismatch,
iSER's prefix is updated to match iSCSIs prefix.
The related changes:
  1. cinder/brick/iscsi/iscsi.py line 614
  2. Cinder/volume/driver.py line 118
  3. etc/cinder/cinder.conf.sample line 921

Closes-Bug: #1336648

commit_message:
Set ZAQAR_BACKEND in localrc if present

In order to add more gates on different backends for Zaqar, we need to
set the ZAQAR_BACKEND env var in devstack. Setting it in the job is not
enough since we need to teach devstack-gate.sh what to do with it. This
patch does exactly that. The ZAQAR_BACKEND variable will be appended to
localrc if it's been set.

Change-Id: Ie629d6233798bd44663dfddb3ec02e3cdc1a69fe

'}, {'created': '2014-09-16 14:20:31.000000000', 'message': 'VMware: Cleanup calls to _move_to_cache() in vmops

Every vmops._cache_*() function calls _move_to_cache() with identical
arguments as its last operation. In fact, on _cache_sparse_image()
does anything other than call _move_to_cache().

This patch pulls the _move_to_cache() call into common code.
_cache_flat_image() and _cache_iso_image() become no-ops, and are
removed. The remaining function, _cache_sparse_image() no longer
caches the image, so is renamed to _process_sparse_image().

Change-Id: I6de899b46b8de2941c7c44a41ae93465e4b4c4d5

'}, {'created': '2014-09-29 14:31:58.000000000', 'message': 'VMware: Cleanup calls to _move_to_cache() in vmops

Every vmops._cache_*() function calls _move_to_cache() with identical
arguments as its last operation. In fact, on _cache_sparse_image()
does anything other than call _move_to_cache().

This patch pulls the _move_to_cache() call into common code.
_cache_flat_image() and _cache_iso_image() become no-ops, and are

commit_message:
VMware: Cleanup calls to _move_to_cache() in vmops

Every vmops._cache_*() function calls _move_to_cache() with identical
arguments as its last operation. In fact, on _cache_sparse_image()
does anything other than call _move_to_cache().

This patch pulls the _move_to_cache() call into common code.
_cache_flat_image() and _cache_iso_image() become no-ops, and are
removed. The remaining function, _cache_sparse_image() no longer
caches the image, so is renamed to _process_sparse_image().

Change-Id: I6de899b46b8de2941c7c44a41ae93465e4b4c4d5

commit_message:
VMware: pass tmp_dir_loc to vmops._prepare_*

Every vmops._prepare_*() is currently calculating tmp_dir_loc. This
patch calculates tmp_dir_loc in common code and passes it in.

Change-Id: I0b36d50968130fdee5c0bdda165940ed362ae7b1

commit_message:
A couple of hot fixes for fuel-agent

1) Fix cloud-init meta-data templates

Just meta-data comments layout.

2) Fix repos handling in nailgun drivers

Remove quotes from urls since apt refuses to work with them.

3) Fix ntp.conf issue

Wrong semaphore ids in boothook were wrong
Closes-Bug: #1388042

Implements: blueprint image-based-provisioning
Change-Id: Iad6755753cc1fa938b370016cd2f4026e76b90a3

commit_message:
Using of $(PRODUCT_VERSION) dependent upstream mirrors

This feature allows to freeze version of upstream mirrors
for each version of product separately.

Closes-Bug: #1377125
Change-Id: I2df5fe9c00aad06dd355c4ea0c956648f0ce2eaf

angular-cookies.js and angular-mock.js have separate xstastic repos. I haven't checked other files. Could you clarify?

I am not sure when we merge 1.2.16 xstasic package because there is no version cap for Juno requirements.txt."}, {'account_id': 8648, 'date': '2014-10-08 09:29:07.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

There were initially separate packages for xstatic-angular-cookies and xstatic-angular-mock, because those were the only other files from angular that Horizon bundled, and it wasn't clear to me whether they are separate libraries or just parts of Angular itself. Turns out that they are parts of Angular and that people using Angular need to use more of those parts, so I decided that the sane thing is to bundle them up in a single package. I also upgraded the two other xstatic-packages for backwards compatibility, but the plan is to discontinue them in the next version."}, {'account_id': 8648, 'date': '2014-10-08 09:30:07.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

commit_message:
Fix KeystoneClient issue when token was expired

KeystoneClient should always first try to use username/password and only if
they are not provided, do a fallback to this.token. Otherwise for expired
tokens login is not possible.

Related-Bug: #1375622
(cherry picked from commit d8d9d96608f759d765ec0b1016e7363229ffc35a)

Change-Id: Ibdaff8d8b7e71e624776d39c95aa8922f1872306

commit_message:
Remove storing of password in browser

Plaintext password was stored in localStorage. This was removed and replaced
by token.
Username is still stored -- we display it in the navigation bar.
Tests were updated to use only the token and a check for username in navbar
was added.

Implements: blueprint access-control-master-node-improvments
(cherry picked from commit c1ee8dfede79b354601f389a91a7244a2920945a)

Conflicts:
	nailgun/static/js/app.js
	nailgun/static/js/views/dialogs.jsx
	nailgun/static/js/views/layout.jsx
	nailgun/static/js/views/login_page.jsx

Change-Id: I2f6edb847e87073dfbe49778a90998c44abc6e34

If you don't have (or provide) the wrong image, KeyName,

Since Icehouse, Heat has has a "custom constraints" method
of dynamically validating parameter values, by comparing the
value provided with a list from the underlying service.

Despite the name, there's nothing "custom" about the constraints,
these ones are included in Heat by default (though they are pluggable,
which is where the name comes from..)

See the docs for more info:

Note, I've not considered network validation here, this could
possibly be added in a subsequent patch.

- heat template-validate -f <template>

commit_message:
Use parameter constraints for image, key and flavor

If you don't have (or provide) the wrong image, KeyName,
or flavor, we fail at some later point (not always early,
depending on what's wrong).

Since Icehouse, Heat has had a "custom constraints" method
of dynamically validating parameter values, by comparing the
value provided with a list from the underlying service.

Despite the name, there's nothing "custom" about the constraints,
these ones are included in Heat by default (though they are pluggable,
which is where the name comes from..)

See the docs for more info:
http://docs.openstack.org/developer/heat/template_guide/hot_spec.html#custom-constraint

Note, I've not considered network validation here, this could
possibly be added in a subsequent patch.

These constraints are evaluated via any of the following:
- heat template-validate -f <template>
- heat stack-preview <arguments given to create>
- heat stack-create <arguments, fails fast before creating anything>
- heat stack-update <arguments, fails fast before updating anything>

Change-Id: I3a6374ce5421575cdde893c62aa97c750a07acd8

commit_message:
Propose Isolate Scheduler DB Aggregates

This spec supports the move to split out the Nova scheduler. Aggregate
information is used by several filters in the filter scheduler
but is populated and manipulated by the AggregateAPI sub-component of the
compute api. To facilitate the split the information needs to be communicated
to the scheduler via an API.

blueprint isolate-scheduler-db-aggregates

Change-Id: Ib12b3ae2b59b6d3bf89a4500226da230f0112a45

Currently mount_check is set to false in Swift's account, container
and object -server.conf files.  This is because by default TripleO
Swift does not use mounted devices for data storage.  However
we (HP) and likely others are in the process of deploying TripleO
on servers which use mounted devices for data storage.  To
accommodate this, we propose to set mount_check to the Heat

commit_message:
Parametrize Swift mount_check setting

Currently mount_check is set to false in Swift's account, container
and object -server.conf files.  This is because by default TripleO
Swift does not use mounted devices for data storage.  However
we (HP) and likely others are in the process of deploying TripleO
on servers which use mounted devices for data storage.  To
accommodate this, we propose to set mount_check to the Heat
metadata swift.mount-check if it exists, otherwise mount_check is
set to false.  We will submit corresponding Heat template changes
to set swift.mount-check, with a default value of false.

Change-Id: I6a67c49120b5dfa95d28d71eb7f9049946e9c5aa

commit_message:
Remove redundancies between neutron-router and neutron-network-node

This change removes the redundancies created by the introduction of the
neutron-router as part of enabling Neutron DVR support in tripleo. Now
rather than installing the l3-agent and metadata-agent as part of the
neutron-network-node element, the element instead has a dependency on
the neutron-router element which does the desired agent installations.

Change-Id: Ief61d028fa3b0674b44d8fb94f585209fd7dc635
blueprint: support-neutron-dvr

commit_message:
Add requirement for APIImpact flag

Adds a requirement for an APIImpact flag in
the commit message for a proposed spec if it proposes
changes to the Barbican REST API. This will make it
much easier for people such as the API WG who want to
review API changes across OpenStack to find and
review proposed API changes.

Change-Id: I73734fa775b3bf25c6eb64311d7940f5db9d5f22

commit_message:
Create 'neutron-router' image element

To enable Neutron DVR support, this change introduces the 'neutron-router'
image element, which mirrors the current 'neutron-network-node' element
except it does not have a dependency on the neutron-dhcp-agent element
as that element should not be included on the compute nodes in the
Neutron Distributed Virtual Routing model.

Change-Id: I487ece637b75f8ef3ce0390f2da093b9f123a8d9
blueprint: support-neutron-dvr

commit_message:
Support adding extra routes when creating subnets

os_cloud_config.neutron.create_subnet will already add a route for
the special cloud-init IP to the metadata server, but we should
allow operators to specify extra routes when creating subnets.

Change-Id: Ic755a31b639454b3b67502090b57ac31eaee45f0

I used entities because for all but one case the same technical description language otherwise appeared in 2-3 places in the document. I felt that:

1. Omitting the description of this (currently defined by STACK_NAME_FORMAT) from any of the 3 calls which currently use it would leave the documentation incomplete.

2. Duplicating the language would run a higher risk of failing to update all uses of it simultaneously, should it ever need to be expanded.

The one case where language is not duplicated is the text added around the reference to STACK_NAME_FORMAT within STACK_NAME_PREVIEW_DESC. commit_message:
Define the stack name for create and preview

The constraints for the stack name were previously undocumented. This
change defines the value for operations that create or preview a stack.

Change-Id: I3eb4bb611a7267bd421905586f17da1f3e5050ae

commit_message:
Load session from builtin session loader

Session now has standard options for loading from a config file. Use
those instead.

DocImpact: This renames the http_connect_timeout config options to
simply timeout.

Change-Id: Ie85f346a9882e3cc9e1a17d88abf7203d3b43787

I've tried to address the last review comment (on the old patchset): 

On Sep 24 2:27 PM, Jeremy Stanley wrote:	

The only bit I see missing is that we're currently overriding node types for jobs (to deal with the icehouse=precise/juno=trusty conundrum) by using regular expression matches in the modules/openstack_project/files/zuul/openstack_functions.py file so you should update that too. Otherwise these jobs are going to show up NOT_REGISTERED when Zuul tries to find Gearman workers other than the ones Jenkins is registering these jobs with.

</end quote>

I've modified the template to include the node name, and have set it to 'centos7' in the case of the AMQP1.0 tests as EL7 should have all the correct packages.  I originally had it set to devstack-f20, but that would pattern-match against the 'f20_re' case in set_node_options(), which appears to skip the devstack configuration.

Really not sure if this is correct, so I'd like some feedback, thanks!"}, {'account_id': 6547, 'date': '2014-09-26 17:39:06.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2: Code-Review-1

commit_message:
Add tests to verify oslo.messaging's AMQP 1.0 protocol support

This non-voting job runs a set of functional tests for AMQP 1.0
support via tox. Since AMQP 1.0 requires system-specific libraries
installed on the host, these tests are run on a properly configured
devstack VM.  These AMQP 1.0 libraries are not yet available for all
node types.  Therefore the tests override the default devstack node
type to 'centos7', as Fedora20+ and EL7 support the latest AMQP 1.0
libraries

Change-Id: I0b4a0c225eee5f6ac017d9397fb748251daedc2e
Implements: blueprint amqp10-driver-implementation

Thanks.'}, {'account_id': 6773, 'date': '2014-10-22 09:39:11.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1: Code-Review+2

Hi Ruby,

Thanks for the patch, it LGTM. I'm not approving cause I'd like to give others the opportunity to see it as well, I'm wondering whether changing the option from string to list would break some backward compat, but it doesn't seem so because because it was a string but treated as a list."}, {'account_id': 3099, 'date': '2014-10-22 11:25:16.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

I like adding versatility, as this patch does, but I think there is something to be said for predictability, too. I'm not sure if it even matters, but it leaves me feeling a little uncomfortable not being able to predict which glance server would be used (again, may not be an issue for *real* operators). I've worked with libraries that did something similar to this (python-gearman, in particular) and the randomness of which server was chosen seemed to always cause issues with tracing problems.

Would a predictable round-robin (using the order specified in the config) work better? Or maybe even always use the first glance server unless it is unavailable, and THEN fall back to the next one, and so on?"}, {'account_id': 3099, 'date': '2014-10-22 11:31:39.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

One more thought, as I'm about to leave for a conference...

As an example of where the randomness might be bad: I haven't looked at our code to see what we do if a glance server is out of commission, but if we fail somehow (throw an exception, report error, etc), wouldn't it be strange for an operator to see that *sometimes* things work and sometimes they don't? Maybe we could add a check up front to test server connectivity before returning the chosen server, which would help no matter what algorithm is used to select a server (random, round robin, etc)."}, {'account_id': 6618, 'date': '2014-10-22 12:59:17.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

So David has some valid points. I took the approach I did, because the code had been originally copy/pasted from Nova/Cinder (which uses the random shuffle and iterator), but something got lost in that copy/paste. Also, if that code becomes oslo-ified (which would be nice), it'd make it easier to migrate to. 

It seems to me that you'd want to put the glance API servers behind a VIP anyway. The question is why someone would specify a list of servers, and if they did, what that meant. I don't actually know/think the random shuffle is needed, but I think iterating makes sense. Especially if there is code to retry talking to Glance."}, {'account_id': 6618, 'date': '2014-10-22 13:00:07.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

@Ghe. Wondering if you have any comments on this approach.'}, {'account_id': 2889, 'date': '2014-10-23 20:53:42.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Code-Review+1

Our retry and exception handling around glance clients has changed from Nova's, so oslo'ifying them won't be entirely straight forward. Overall though, the code is still fairly similar.

I agree that one should put glance API servers behind a load balancer with some monitoring in place to remove API services that are not responsive. That's a bog-standard thing to do. The retry logic within both Ironic and Nova should handle that reasonably well.... so I am left to think that this round-robin retry stuff is there as a "poor man's alternative" to using a load balancer.

As David pointed out, this approach will also lead to unpredictable behavior (1/Nth of deploys failing) if a glance API server becomes unreachable.

I am only +1 on this, because it adds functionality which is only marginally useful for small deployments, and adds complexity in debugging. I'm not convinced it's a good trade off, but I'm not against it strongly either.'}, {'account_id': 6618, 'date': '2014-10-23 21:17:29.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

Here are the choices (I think):

1. do nothing (not a choice so don't even think about it)

2. allow only one API server. Deprecate 'glance_api_servers', and use 'glance_api_server' instead

3. allow multiple API servers
   3a. iterate over them using the order specified
   3b. randomize the list first, and then iterate over them

I am fine with 2 or any 3, just not 1 :-)"}, {'account_id': 8125, 'date': '2014-10-23 22:46:32.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1: Code-Review+1

(1 comment)

I agree with the other review comments raised, but I'm fine with this going ahead.  Thanks Ruby."}, {'account_id': 6773, 'date': '2014-10-24 11:06:40.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

I'm fine with this change, I'm +1 to have the 3b) (just as is). I agree with @David and @Devananda comments and I see how it may impacting on debbuging, but I think that this behavior is expected when working with a cloud application, we should not care where/which glance instance the image is going to end up."}, {'account_id': 7491, 'date': '2014-10-24 13:31:38.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Code-Review+1

looks good, a single question inline.'}, {'account_id': 7882, 'date': '2014-10-27 04:18:32.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Code-Review+1'}, {'account_id': 3099, 'date': '2014-10-27 13:09:17.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1: Code-Review+1

[{'created': '2014-10-21 17:39:19.000000000', 'message': "Iterate over glance API servers

The configuration option CONF.glance.glance_api_servers is meant to
be a list of Glance API servers, and should behave similar to its use
in Nova and Cinder: that each time a Glance API server is wanted, one
of the servers in the list is returned.

This changes CONF.glance.glance_api_servers to be a list instead of
a string. The list is randomly shuffled, and an iterator is
used to cycle through the list of servers.

This is backwards compatible and handles the case where the
user may have set [glance]/glance_api_servers = 'host:port' (or
'host1:port1, host2:port2'). The configuration library will
convert that to the corresponding list.

Closes-Bug: #1381135

Change-Id: Ic7cab502f38407aa0c282203804023dfa45b6623
"}]
commit_message:
Iterate over glance API servers

The configuration option CONF.glance.glance_api_servers is meant to
be a list of Glance API servers, and should behave similar to its use
in Nova and Cinder: that each time a Glance API server is wanted, one
of the servers in the list is returned.

This changes CONF.glance.glance_api_servers to be a list instead of
a string. The list is randomly shuffled, and an iterator is
used to cycle through the list of servers.

This is backwards compatible and handles the case where the
user may have set [glance]/glance_api_servers = 'host:port' (or
'host1:port1, host2:port2'). The configuration library will
convert that to the corresponding list.

Closes-Bug: #1381135

Change-Id: Ic7cab502f38407aa0c282203804023dfa45b6623

The Cisco Nexus ML2 MD overwrites any existing switchport
VLAN config such as management VLANs that are preconfigured
in the compute node ToR interfaces.
This bug addresses that issue and ensures the config is not
wiped out.

Change-Id: Ie2969e5750a179a4940d12db4c9ee6e1ec53b79b

commit_message:
ML2 Cisco Nexus MD - not overwriting existing config

The Cisco Nexus ML2 MD overwrites any existing switchport
VLAN config such as management VLANs that are preconfigured
in the compute node ToR interfaces.
This bug addresses that issue and ensures the config is not
wiped out.

Closes-Bug: 1330597

Change-Id: Ie2969e5750a179a4940d12db4c9ee6e1ec53b79b

commit_message:
Remove incorrect auto-generated wording

The generated documentation for several calls includes wording that the
call does not return a response body, when in fact the call does return
a response body. This change removes the incorrect wording; the
documentation will need to be updated separately to described the
actual response body.

Change-Id: I3d6ad79a4f4214e3e6f67a1a0c45359f3c36da62

[{'created': '2014-09-29 12:47:42.000000000', 'message': 'Provide script functionality for creating update mirrors

Update mirrors are the differences between versions
 We have several ways for creating mirrors:
 1) simple comparation of two mirror folders (the easyest way)
   Should be run on server (or client) where we have two
   ready mirrors (for example for ver. 5.1 and 6.0)
   6.0 - 5.1 = update_mirror
 2) more complex implementation (good for make process)
   in this case we build PRODUCT_VERSION mirror and then
   download and process the difference in packages
   between PRODUCT_VERSION..master (Works good for RPM,
   not so good fo DEB).

Implements-blueprint: generating-update-mirrors
Change-Id: Ic208b28e87a1505fe12317494ad327841c9a0964

commit_message:
Reducing the size of upgrade tarball

* implemented building diff mirrors
* defined diff mirror artifacts
* put diff mirrors into upgrade tarball

Implements-blueprint: generating-update-mirrors
Change-Id: Ic208b28e87a1505fe12317494ad327841c9a0964

commit_message:
Implement persistence of iptables on reboot

Use the iptables-persistent package
to implement persistence of iptables during a reboot
for Ubuntu and Debian.
Entries are saved to /etc/iptables/rules* on add-rule.
These entries are restored on reboot.
( Note in later versions iptables-persistent is replaced
by netfilter-persistent with plugins in iptables-persistent)

Change-Id: I44b625111d5db34a444c5aa4f6e31c6009c8a6f5

commit_message:
drop deprecated oslo-incubator middleware

- openstack.common.middleware has graduated to oslo.middleware. this
patch changes default to oslo.middleware
- the replaced middleware is updated to reflect deprecated
functionality but left intact to allow for backwards compatibility
and grenade testing

Change-Id: I3858d500c8b8bc3db81ee4eecd44d15c0a771f65

[{'created': '2014-10-14 23:43:07.000000000', 'message': "Clean up seed image file

Since libvirt doesn't manage the seed's storage volume, it doesn't
currently get deleted when cleanup-env is run. This change handles the
destroy and volume cleanup differently for the seed such that the volume
gets removed.

Changes have also been added in the destroy and remove process to avoid
producing noisy error messages, by only destroying domains that are
currently running, as well as only attempting to remove storage for
non-seed domains.

Change-Id: I65b8f5dde936efa11c0b6857a5b8b138da7f425b
Closes-Bug: 1298466
"}]
commit_message:
Clean up seed image file

Since libvirt doesn't manage the seed's storage volume, it doesn't
currently get deleted when cleanup-env is run. This change handles the
destroy and volume cleanup differently for the seed such that the volume
gets removed.

Changes have also been added in the destroy and remove process to avoid
producing noisy error messages, by only destroying domains that are
currently running, as well as only attempting to remove storage for
non-seed domains.

Change-Id: I65b8f5dde936efa11c0b6857a5b8b138da7f425b
Closes-Bug: 1298466

commit_message:
Reducing the size of upgrade tarball

* implemented building diff mirrors
* defined diff mirror artifacts
* put diff mirrors into upgrade tarball

Implements-blueprint: generating-update-mirrors
Change-Id: Ic208b28e87a1505fe12317494ad327841c9a0964

'}, {'created': '2014-10-15 15:38:23.000000000', 'message': 'Add ability to build separate fs images

This patch is required to build images for every separate mountpoint needed
both for centos and ubuntu.
Eg. /boot, /var, /var/lib, etc.
File system support is limited to ext2, ext3, ext4 only.
No XFS support mainly because of unexpectly consumed free space and absence of
working resizing tools due to that.

Controlled by SEPARATE_IMAGES environment variable. String format should be
space separated list with comma separated mountpoint and filesystem type. Eg.:
SEPARATE_IMAGES="/boot,ext2 /,ext4 /var,ext3"
Defaults to "/boot,ext2 /,ext4". Notice, that at least separate /boot is
required for operating of image based provisioning.

Implements: blueprint image-based-provisioning
Change-Id: I650052154fe7b483aaba89389e9a09f80fc1543e

commit_message:
Add ability to build separate fs images

This patch is required to build images for every separate mountpoint needed
both for centos and ubuntu.
Eg. /boot, /var, /var/lib, etc.
File system support is limited to ext2, ext3, ext4 only.
No XFS support mainly because of unexpectly consumed free space and absence of
working resizing tools due to that.

Controlled by SEPARATE_IMAGES environment variable. String format should be
space separated list with comma separated mountpoint and filesystem type. Eg.:
SEPARATE_IMAGES="/boot,ext2 /,ext4 /var,ext3"
Defaults to "/boot,ext2 /,ext4". Notice, that at least separate /boot is
required for operating of image based provisioning.

Implements: blueprint image-based-provisioning

commit_message:
Don't pass client_encoding to postgresql on rhel6

It doesn't support it, and it causes it to fail.

Change-Id: Ie76fdd2f2abbbf6e250cf5c7a00c3d0fd88368f8

commit_message:
Use oslo.middleware

Remove outdated code and replace its usages by usages of oslo.middleware
library

Sync latest request_id middleware from oslo-incubator(only to allow
grenade jobs pass)

4ffc4c8 Add middleware.request_id shim for Kilo
4504e4f Remove middleware

Co-Authored-By: Abhishek Chanda <abhishek@cloudscaling.com>
Co-Authored-By: Davanum Srinivas <dims@linux.vnet.ibm.com>

Change-Id: I89ef3df1b8d3b2c6e391d04e89e35f2ee974a3cc

commit_message:
Remove param check for backup type on v2.1 API

The backup type is only used by glance, so nova check it make
no sense; currently we have daily and weekly as only valid param
but someone may add 'monthly' as param. nova should allow it
and delegate the error. This patch removes check on v2.1 API.

Change-Id: I59bbc0f589c8c280eb8cd87aa279898fffaeab7a
Closes-Bug: #1361490

Remove uncessary instance.save in nova compute

Adjust the code path to remove an uncessary instance.save
function to make the boot performance better.

commit_message:
VMware: use instance.uuid instead of instance['uuid']

Uses an instance object for deletion, port attach and detach.
These methods now receive an instance object instead of a dict.

TrivialFix

Change-Id: I1092d32f5144baac6dfdc919f5e827533c67e6d6

commit_message:
Deprecate PKI setup in init-keystone

The initialize() method in os_cloud_config.keystone has a flag to
configure if PKI setup is performed or not. Since devtest is moving
to another script to perform PKI setup, we can deprecate doing it
in init-keystone, and also add options to control if it runs or not
from the command line.

Change-Id: Iefc9b367c9844342a42ddf055b35bb7c242742b9

commit_message:
Add the --no-mergepy option

Passing `--no-mergepy` to devtest or devtest_overcloud, will use the
standalone templates (overcloud-without-mergepy.yaml and friends) instead of
building overcloud.yaml by running merge.py on overcloud-source.yaml.

Since the standalone templates rely on a resource registry specified in a
separate Heat environment file (overcloud-resource-registry.yaml), this feature
requires python-heatclient version 0.2.11 which added support for passing
multiple environment files to `heat`.

Change-Id: Ib82eecf0998ae5c0a811a248b638c5633c8bb262

If we are creating a tagged provider network, we don't want Neutron
providing a dhcpd on an enterprise or public network, so turn it
off.

Drive-by a spelling correction of 'tenant'.

Change-Id: I1dad5e65983839066b472ad6f634cf2ef51c715c
"}, {'created': '2014-10-27 03:51:55.000000000', 'message': "Permit configuration of DHCP when creating subnets

Allow operators to control if a subnet will have DHCP enabled by
adding support for a 'enable_dhcp' boolean, which will get passed
down to Neutron when creating the subnet.

Drive-by a spelling correction of 'tenant'.

Change-Id: I1dad5e65983839066b472ad6f634cf2ef51c715c
"}]
commit_message:
Permit configuration of DHCP when creating subnets

Allow operators to control if a subnet will have DHCP enabled by
adding support for a 'enable_dhcp' boolean, which will get passed
down to Neutron when creating the subnet.

Drive-by a spelling correction of 'tenant'.

Change-Id: I1dad5e65983839066b472ad6f634cf2ef51c715c

commit_message:
Add heat-templates to pull-tools

The heat-templates repo has a set of elements
in hot/software-config/elements that are very
useful for alternative software-config hooks.

Some of us are starting to make use of these
elements on a daily basis so it would be nice to have
them automatically updated via pull-tools.

Change-Id: I38a304242f57bf37946b6a4fa009ffd47466182f

commit_message:
Building OS images centos and ubuntu

Those images are supposed to be used for
image based provisioning. This patch set
needs python-imgcreate package to be available.
Manual workaround is used to make
separate images for / and /boot for centos.

Images are only to be built if experimental
feature group is enabled.

Implements: blueprint image-based-provisioning
Change-Id: I4f038c99d4caf7d2b6e291bff29572b3a45d92c7

Comment on testing:

We have unit tests such as the following which check some of the code paths, eg
to verify that 'auth_token' was set:

 class TestMultiTenantStoreConnections(base.StoreBaseTest):
    def setUp(self):
        super(TestMultiTenantStoreConnections, self).setUp()
        moxfixture = self.useFixture(moxstubout.MoxStubout())
        self.stubs = moxfixture.stubs
        self.stubs.Set(swiftclient, 'Connection', FakeConnection)
        self.context = context.RequestContext(
            user='tenant:user1', tenant='tenant', auth_token='0123')
        self.store = swift.MultiTenantStore(self.conf)
        specs = {'scheme': 'swift',
                 'auth_or_store_url': 'example.com',
                 'container': 'cont',
                 'obj': 'object'}
        self.location = swift.StoreLocation(specs, self.conf)
        self.addCleanup(self.conf.reset)

unfortunately this isn't as complete as real end-to-end testing of the glance<->glance_store code path which would have caught image upload/download issues.

We do have some swift integration tests in glance (enabled when GLANCE_TEST_SWIFT_CONF is set) but these are not run as part of the gate and so tend to fall into disrepair.

A tempest job which had the swift store enabled in multi-tenant node would be a big help to prevent regression around token behaviour."}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2014-10-28 17:12:41.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2: Verified+1

commit_message:
Swift Multi-tenant store: Pass context on upload

Image upload returns an E500 as the context is not being
passed to the swift client.
