commit_message:
[Sahara] Copy policy.json if it exists

To enable policy check in Sahara we need gate tests passed.
Tests will not pass until Sahara has default policy.json (
e.g. http://logs.openstack.org/09/131609/1/check/check-tempest-dsvm-full/536d5e7/console.html). 
New code will copy of policy.json if it exists.

So, for now this code will do nothing.
Once policy.json appears in etc/sahara, the code will start coping
it to sahara conf dir. This will allow to merge auth support with
gate tests passed.

Related blueprint: auth-policy

Change-Id: I98e108ff02aacb91570f97e457d67dd02779ae3d

commit_message:
Refactor the stop operation for neutron-dhcp-agent

* Combine the stopping of neutron-dhcp-agent and the stopping of dnsmasq
processes inside namespaces into one time period (it was only for stopping
of ONE neutron dhcp process).
* Clean up duplicate code .

Change-Id: Iaaa2b6f7c8e3b0fa870715c69fd39fa45e5dc526
Closes-Bug: 1377906

commit_message:
Add logging to driver vendor_passthru functions

Since the drivers' vendor_passthru are async. calls, any exceptions
raised by them won't be handled. So all exceptions, even non-Ironic
exceptions should be logged.

This patch adds a decorator that can be used to wrap passthru function
calls and ensure that any exceptions get logged correctly, also adds
unit tests to ensure decorators functionality.

Change-Id: I17006611fd59d5f4dc78fdaefdf802e9fb7caff2
Implements: blueprint extended-vendor-passthru
Closes-Bug: 1372979

commit_message:
Add python-keystonemiddleware package to OSTF spec

OSTF now requires keystonemiddleware package to use it
instead of outdated keystoneclient.middleware

Update python-keystoneclient version to match version in
our repos

Change-Id: I32848ccd2279c1467818e1ff9e1a19becc9f7ae7
Implements: blueprint access-control-master-node-improvments
Related-Bug: #1383616

[{'created': '2014-10-22 16:54:36.000000000', 'message': 'Automatically expand and shrink eventlet greenpool

Added a new option to make eventlet executor expand and shrink its
greenthread pool to accomodate all active threads instead of blocking their
execution until pool is not overflowed.

Enabled the option by default.

blueprint expand-and-shrink-eventlet-greenpool

Change-Id: I75129caf0c090e5e6dc0c56aea1021bda61ec0dd
Related-Bug: 1372049
'}, {'created': '2014-10-24 16:38:40.000000000', 'message': "Raise the number of RPC threads to run in parallel

Once greenthread pool is full, it will block execution of new threads
until some of active threads complete their execution.

The default value (64) is too low for some types of load when threads
are I/O bound, waiting for an external entity to reply. One of examples
is Nova booting multiple instances in parallel, that results in lots of
requests to Neutron to bind ports for them. This process may take a
while, so in the meantime Nova is blocked to proceed with booting more
instances, and eventually some of boot requests fail due to timeout.

Increasing the size of a greenthread pool does not mean booking of any
system resources, so we're free to set any number without being afraid
of hitting some resource limit.

That said, high parallelism may have its drawbacks in some scenarios.
For example, if each thread opens a lot of file descriptors, and there
are lots of them executing in one single time, we can end up hitting
process limit on opened fds, which is 1024 by default on Linux. So
assuming each thread opens a pipe at the same time (which usually uses
three fds), we're safe to run 1024/3 ~ 341 threads without hitting the
limit.

The change conservatively raises the size of the pool to 256 which
should be enough for loads we currently envision. We may return back to
the value if we hit the next limit.

Related-Bug: #1372049
Change-Id: I75129caf0c090e5e6dc0c56aea1021bda61ec0dd
"}]
commit_message:
Raise the number of RPC threads to run in parallel

Once greenthread pool is full, it will block execution of new threads
until some of active threads complete their execution.

The default value (64) is too low for some types of load when threads
are I/O bound, waiting for an external entity to reply. One of examples
is Nova booting multiple instances in parallel, that results in lots of
requests to Neutron to bind ports for them. This process may take a
while, so in the meantime Nova is blocked to proceed with booting more
instances, and eventually some of boot requests fail due to timeout.

Increasing the size of a greenthread pool does not mean booking of any
system resources, so we're free to set any number without being afraid
of hitting some resource limit.

That said, high parallelism may have its drawbacks in some scenarios.
For example, if each thread opens a lot of file descriptors, and there
are lots of them executing in one single time, we can end up hitting
process limit on opened fds, which is 1024 by default on Linux. So
assuming each thread opens a pipe at the same time (which usually uses
three fds), we're safe to run 1024/3 ~ 341 threads without hitting the
limit.

The change conservatively raises the size of the pool to 256 which
should be enough for loads we currently envision. We may return back to
the value if we hit the next limit.

Related-Bug: #1372049
Change-Id: I75129caf0c090e5e6dc0c56aea1021bda61ec0dd

commit_message:
Enable the PBM WSDL to be updated

Enables the PBM WSDL to be updated after a session is created.

An update of the WSDL will set the pbm value to None. This is lazy loaded
so the next access to it will result in the correct session being created.

Change-Id: Id70a7928ca84846018ee0a62ac020ecbeac1f5d6

commit_message:
SAML2 wrapper plugin for full federation authN

For a better user experience a SAML2 wrapper plugin tries to
hide federated authentication workflow details and automatically
load underlying plugins, retrieve unscoped token and scope it to a
desired project_id or domain_id. In case invalid data is passed
the plugin will pass forward exceptions and error messages raised by
corresponding plugins.

Change-Id: I1309e08e58b3958209dd248a3905e9f6f91da728
Implements: blueprint add-saml2-cli-authentication

commit_message:
Fix error raising in cfn with wrong output section

There is a situation, when output object in cfn template
has empty body. In this situation we got traceback instead
of error message, this is incorrect. Furthermore, if output
body is a string, we got traceback too. Follow AWS template
format docs (UserGuide), every output object must contain
property 'Value'. So corresponding error should be raised.

Change-Id: I0d7e3e57e479ddb658645b8664bc847866180cda
Closes-bug: #1386332

Dom0's bash does not support associative arrays, however we source
`functions` and therefore our scripts fail. This change breaks the
dependency of dom0 scripts on domU functions. The patch has impact
mainly around neutron installation:
 - Always create an integration network. Before this change, the network
   was only created if neutron enabled. As the `is_service_enabled`
   function is not available and the dependency on DomU settings is
   broken, there is no way to check the condition.
 - Move openvswitch agent's xapi plugin installation to domU. Use the
   same mechanism as used for installing the nova plugins.
 - Remove non-used functions

Fixes bug: 1379804

commit_message:
XenAPI: workaround for unsupp. associative arrays

Dom0's bash does not support associative arrays, however we source
`functions` and therefore our scripts fail. This change breaks the
dependency of dom0 tools on domU functions.

Fixes bug: 1379804

Change-Id: I229e2d5f07070a9236ec612d4032c94c4361a9f6

commit_message:
XenAPI: move Neutron plugin install to domU

Use the same mechanism as used for nova plugin installation, thus
avoiding the need for variables in dom0. This change will also help to
move XenServer CI to neutron in the future, as the dom0 part of the
script is not executed there.

With this change, the neutron related network will always be created and
attached even if the user wants to use nova-network.

Change-Id: I8669c94e9f0aacce2990469dbabde1ff702a2769

commit_message:
Enable Swift's newer feature of container-sync

Newer version of container-sync feature is introduced in Swift ver. 1.12.0.

The spec:
http://docs.openstack.org/developer/swift/overview_container_sync.html

Before this commit, Devstack does not configure any realm used in
container-sync, therefore this feature does not work.
To test this feature in CI system, moreover to show the sample
configuration of realms, Devstack now edits realms configuration file.

Change-Id: I9f1e3224403e08e725a989162729470357fe90b0
Closes-Bug: 1378646
(cherry picked from commit d03915f9c08ff91c5d39f8cadb064718079bdb4b)

commit_message:
Create Data Sources panel in Horizon

Move existing Policies panel under a new Policy panel group. Add new Data
Sources panel, moving list of policy tables from the old Policy panel there.
Modify devstack script to update Horizon for running unit tests and README to
include Ceilometer services. Fix bug with wrapping Policy object twice in
congress.py:policy_get().

Implements: blueprint horizon-read-datasources
Change-Id: I3fe684d91d079ad1288f97b4e048c11b5edf986a

commit_message:
Return verbose message if account quota exceeded

This message is already used in the container quota middleware, so let's use it
in the account middleware too.

Change-Id: I136fe6102c28cc8ccc021555c42ec7b0be716444
Closes-Bug: 1381875

Swift Multi-tenant store: Fix image upload

Image upload returns an E500 as the token is not being
passed to the swift client.

Closes-bug: #1385213

commit_message:
Configure glance CA certificate path in cinder

A new configuration option is available in cinder for setting
the CA path. Configure this option in devstack when native SSL
or TLS proxy is configured.

Change-Id: I2cf9a3b8ba8e4896bd98efe0fb6f7d62fb279d90
Closes-Bug: 1384267

commit_message:
correct templated catalog driver class

Now the templated catalog driver class "TemplatedCatalog" is removed
in this patch https://review.openstack.org/#/c/125708/2 use
"keystone.catalog.backends.templated.Catalog" instead.

Change-Id: Ib9c8ea557e7171ff0c78a1e10d752ed564aff9e7
Closes-Bug: #1386562

commit_message:
XenAPI: Always update proxy settings

If a user wants to re-use an xva just with different proxy settings, he
can now do it, as this change will always update /etc/apt/apt.conf to
reflect the settings in the user's localrc.

Change-Id: I8a6e9c88304bc887ea8269d946e89a5ba258b126

commit_message:
Fix a minor comments

A minor mismatch in lib/neutron since now unstack.sh invokes
three functions and also start_neutron_agents() is called before
create_neutron_initial_network().

Change-Id: Ibbe68501cce4c062a9ac610cbc44188dc9bab6c8

commit_message:
Fpb, add validation when user runs build command

* add jsonschema based validation
* changed creation process to make it simpler
  and more versioning friendly
* added MANIFEST.in because in setup.py it's
  impossible to specify directory with subdirectories
  to package the data files
* renamed package to fuel-plugin-builder,
  it's more conventional name for python
  eggs
* created an alias for `fpb` command `fuel-plugin-builder`

Implements: blueprint cinder-neutron-plugins-in-fuel
Change-Id: I76ba45d2176e84f6d12c2a65f563b43b1a415d79

revisions:
[{'created': '2014-10-29 05:28:34.000000000', 'message': 'Move creation of custom env into enironment module

This patch replaces the _nested_environment with a new method in the
environment module.  The intent is to make it easy for some resources

commit_message:
Move creation of custom env to environment module

This patch replaces the _nested_environment with a new method in the
environment module.  The intent is to make it easy for some resources
(such as remote-stack) to use its own environment without having to
subclass from StackResource.

Change-Id: Ice0124aa21086788e957eb708b6bc423779202bc

commit_message:
Add api calls to os in assert_cluster_ready

We should to stop use exec os command over ssh
and start to use python clients for cluster
verification.
This patch includes:
* add some api calls to the helpers.os_action
* checkers.image_list start to use api calls
* checkers.service_list move from nova-message
  usage to nova.services.list()
* checkers.netwotk_list start to use nova.networks.list()
* Test were updated

Change-Id: I2f042b3c8215611ce2c1a6f0cf37ccd03bbdf967
Closes-Bug: #1385420

revisions:
[{'created': '2014-10-30 11:12:26.000000000', 'message': "Fix object-replicator syncing with quoram success

Currentry, object-replicator might not sync its own replica
even if it is different from other primary node's one.
That is because object-replicator and object-server never recalculate
their own local suffix hashes when the local suffixes are in hash.pickles.

This causes to keep inconsistency forever unfortunately among primary replicas
when a PUT request succeeded with quoram successes.

This is the unfortunate case here:

Assuming 3 replica

T0: An object created by a PUT request.
    (all of replicas succeeded)
T1: A hash.pickle created by object-replicator.
T2: The object updated by a PUT request.
    (2 replicas succeeded but 1 replica failed by some reason)
T3: Exisiting hash.pickle was used by object-replictor to check the object existence.
    (Exisiting suffix hashes in hash.pickle are never recalculated)
T4: An object-replicator passes WITHOUT pushing its own local replica to the failure replica.
...
Tn: Each replica never gets its consistency among primary nodes.

This patch fixes object-replicator to recalculate its local
suffix hashes eventually.

Change-Id: I9e19f3689341b720254a4421bf288da88e9d8d08
"}]
commit_message:
Fix object-replicator syncing with quoram success

Currentry, object-replicator might not sync its own replica
even if it is different from other primary node's one.
That is because object-replicator and object-server never recalculate
their own local suffix hashes when the local suffixes are in hash.pickles.

This causes to keep inconsistency forever unfortunately among primary replicas
when a PUT request succeeded with quoram successes.

This is the unfortunate case here:

Assuming 3 replica

T0: An object created by a PUT request.
    (all of replicas succeeded)
T1: A hash.pickle created by object-replicator.
T2: The object updated by a PUT request.
    (2 replicas succeeded but 1 replica failed by some reason)
T3: Exisiting hash.pickle was used by object-replictor to check the object existence.
    (Exisiting suffix hashes in hash.pickle are never recalculated)
T4: An object-replicator passes WITHOUT pushing its own local replica to the failure replica.
...
Tn: Each replica never gets its consistency among primary nodes.

This patch fixes object-replicator to recalculate its local
suffix hashes eventually.

Change-Id: I9e19f3689341b720254a4421bf288da88e9d8d08

commit_message:
Make sure that tox uses python2 by default

Our documentation tools are not python3 compatible, so make sure that
tox creates python2 virtual environments during tests.

Change-Id: I38e62e20c0e42d1d29c9f3b40704455889618530

(3 comments)

Thanks yunhong,

I see this patch and the next one of the series and I think it's a pretty cool feature. One thing that makes me wonder is whether it matters if we convert it to raw or not? Since in the next patch we can convert things on the fly as we deploy it should the user really care what is the image format in Ironic?"}, {'account_id': 4573, 'date': '2014-10-28 17:05:25.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2:

(6 comments)

Hi, Lucas and Yuriy, thanks for review.

Lucas, as for if we want to keep this config, I'd suggest to keep this. There are two reasons for such suggestion. 

Firstly this is added as a workaround for https://bugs.launchpad.net/nova/+bug/932180 by Vish, as for a security reason (I quota that link in the comments, it's https://bugs.launchpad.net/nova/+bug/853330 ), and then  thus I'd keep it untouched. After all, security is always a sensitive topic and I don't want to remove it w/o input from security expert.


Secondly, the force_raw_image is more a trade off of space/time and some user may want to save time. For example, if multiple compute node are using the same image, and the ironic deploy has the master image repo, then there is no need to do the convert each deploy time, instead, it only require one convert when the image is fetched into the image_cache.

Your idea?"}, {'account_id': 4573, 'date': '2014-10-28 21:55:04.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 3.'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2014-10-28 22:45:22.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3:

[{'created': '2014-10-24 20:08:03.000000000', 'message': "Change the force_raw_image config usage

The force_raw_image comes from nova side. The reason of the flag is, after
all images are forced to be raw because of security reason
(https://bugs.launchpad.net/nova/+bug/853330), this flag
is added so that deployer can still select use raw images or compressed
images.

Currently this flag is used in the deeper of functions like image_to_raw() or
converted_size(). For example, image_to_raw() will convert the image
to be raw format only if the force_raw_image flag is set, that means
the caller totally have no idea if the image returned is a raw image or not.

This is possibly ok for libvirt since libvirt does not care for qcow2
or raw, but it's different for ironic, since we will take different action
for qcow2/raw format. A flag in such deeper layer is not so good.

This patch changes these functions, so that the caller in image cache level
accept parameter from deploy level like iscsi_deploy or pxe, which make
decision based on the config.

Change-Id: I118c9d8edcc13d15762593c254eaf27792d6c55f
Related-Bug: #1382164

commit_message:
Change the force_raw_image config usage

The force_raw_image comes from nova side as a
fix for https://bugs.launchpad.net/nova/+bug/1383465.

The reason of the flag is, after all images are forced
to be raw because of security reason
(https://bugs.launchpad.net/nova/+bug/853330), this flag
is added later so that deployer can still select using raw images or
compressed images.

Currently this flag is used in the deeper of functions like image_to_raw() or
converted_size(). For example, image_to_raw() will convert the image
to be raw format only if the force_raw_image flag is set, that means
the caller totally have no idea if the image returned is a raw image or not.

This is possibly ok for libvirt since libvirt does not care for qcow2
or raw, but it's different for ironic, since we will take different action
for qcow2/raw format. A flag in such deeper layer is not so good.

This patch changes these functions, so that the caller in image cache level
accept parameter from deploy level like iscsi_deploy or pxe, which make
decision based on the config.

Change-Id: I118c9d8edcc13d15762593c254eaf27792d6c55f
Related-Bug: #1382164

commit_message:
Cleanly override config in tests

CONF.set_override() is often called in tests but CONF.clear_override()
is never. Create a override_config() method in the base TestCase class
that restores previous conf value after test, as it is done in other
OpenStack projects.

Change-Id: Id57b4502a2a37ea12047985cf2ea6c38c6f965fd

commit_message:
Simplify keepalived custom policy

Instead of allowing access to individual types to keepalived, we
now grant keepalived access to read the processes for all types.

This change was suggested in
https://bugzilla.redhat.com/show_bug.cgi?id=1151647

This also makes the custom policy work on both Fedora and RHEL.
The previous custom policy would not install on RHEL 7.0 because
some types were not defined in 7.0.

Change-Id: Ic7adbd14ef27959f0a991127b5213384c9e46be3

commit_message:
Move group affinity filters tests to own test file

The group affinity filter unit tests remained in the
test_host_filters.py test file. We simply move them to
test_affinity_filters.py in this patch.

Change-Id: Ic10a5ba2875de42f1f83d30e6d9bd982dffc17e4

commit_message:
Use 404 instead of 400 when security_group is non-existed

This patch correct the status code when security_group is
non-existed. This is good for sharing unittest between v2.1
and v2 API.

Change-Id: Ib4bd725381052947859db1ab30905fa33e502679

It is not possible to add a DNS record alone to the Rackspace Cloud DNS
resource because the domain.update() method will be called with no

commit_message:
Check prop_diff contents after modifying it

It is not possible to add a DNS record alone to the Rackspace Cloud DNS
resource because the domain.update() method will be called with no
arguments.  Re-check the contents of prop_diff after modifying it to see
if calling domain.update() is necessary.

Change-Id: I04e313eab7f2d8971e9f12bfb402259b48757919

commit_message:
Glance auth_version needs to be in conf by default

When auth_version value is v2.0, it still should explicitly
set auth_version to v2.0 as the default value in configuration file.
This is also to be consistent with other components. The current
code does not have 'auth_version = v2.0' in the configuration file
if the value is v2.0.

Change-Id: Ic39626f2d40d8ca6f5d5fc5864e5b5407b71d730
Closes-Bug: #1387067

commit_message:
Add more attributes for nova.conf DEFAULT section

Since there are some default options that did not set in nova.conf.erb
file, so add them to ensure users can custom them.

Change-Id: I70c110b0e4d67b25155bb02e96bb8f02b455b3bd

commit_message:
Add converted version of block and object storage

This patch extends the previous 'Don't use merge.py for overcloud'
commit with the cinder-storage.yaml and swift-storage.yaml templates.

Requirements for this to deploy:

1. Block and object storage images have to be built
(overcloud-cinder-volume and overcloud-swift-storage)

2. The images have to be loaded by devtest_overcloud.sh
OVERCLOUD_CINDER_ID=$(load-image -d $TRIPLEO_ROOT/overcloud-cinder-volume.qcow2)
OVERCLOUD_SWIFT_ID=$(load-image -d $TRIPLEO_ROOT/overcloud-swift-storage.qcow2)

Change-Id: I45f9d9f051970a83e26c0fd924d7c98276958113

[{'created': '2014-07-02 22:42:21.000000000', 'message': "Support new virtual_interfaces definition for VIPs

Prior to this change, the keepalived element only allowed for a single
keepalive interface. This could be problematic if, for instance,
keepalive is managing several VIPs which are on different broadcast
domains. This change allows for a more flexible configuration in which
multiple vrrp instances can be defined in heat- each iwth their own
interface, router_id, and set of virtual IPs.

Some of this information is also used by haproxy, so this change also
tweaks haproxy to use the same virtual_interfaces definition (if
provided) in preference to local net_binds.

Local per-port overrides of the IP to bind to can still be provided -
but they'll now have to be put into a local map called
virtual_interfaces rather than a local map called net_binds.

Change-Id: I5f04cee6c84ce7ad6e258c489088a47f00a53fda

commit_message:
Support new virtual_interfaces definition for VIPs

Prior to this change, the keepalived element only allowed for a single
keepalive interface. This could be problematic if, for instance,
keepalive is managing several VIPs which are on different broadcast
domains - for instance, because one vip is on an interface/vlan that's
accessible to the public, while another is on an interface/vlan that's
only accessible within the cloud.

This change allows for a more flexible configuration in which multiple
vrrp instances can be defined in heat- each with their own interface,
router_id, and set of virtual IPs.

This patchset partially completes a spec which will one day live at
https://blueprints.launchpad.net/tripleo/+specs/tripleo-juno-virtual-public-ips
but for now can bee seen in  Id9addc65f0d2ed519ce4b3edbd561ed660a2786e

Removed the check weight configuration as vrrp_sync_groups and and
check_script weights are mutually exclusive configurations. Regardless,
based on
https://github.com/acassen/keepalived/blob/master/doc/keepalived.conf.SYNOPSIS#L103
the default weight is automatically set to 2 if not specified.

Change-Id: I5f04cee6c84ce7ad6e258c489088a47f00a53fda
Co-authored-by: Julia Kreger <juliaashleykreger@gmail.com>

commit_message:
Update Debian repo to retrieve signed Release file

After bootstraping a Debian image, the repository keys
are installed to verify the packages signatures, but the
Release signature file is missing. Updating the repo,
will retrieve a new InRelease file (inline signed).

Change-Id: I14f0d22cc9c72be9b07f3708270359bc8cff112d

commit_message:
Adds misc options

This change adds support for miscellaneous options to be set.
Things that haven't been added as attributes, or specifically,
third party additions that don't belong in stackforge.

Change-Id: I482c5d15e5d1ad853d1a1792f3e39a45f7911dd4

commit_message:
Add pbr to dependency list

Currently pbr is breaking markup safe usage in docs, the
not so obvious way to fix this is to place pbr in the
explicit requirements for pylockfile.

Closes-Bug: #1384919

Change-Id: I0bba2f28956aeeb70b1e15f82d6bb67fdbd49118

commit_message:
Reserve Keystone ports from the ephemeral range

Reserve Keystone ports from the ephemeral range as early as reasonably
possible in the fixup_stuff.sh process to reduce the likelihood that the
port will be in use. This does not completely resolve the issue
where Keystone's IANA assigned port falls into Linux's ephemeral
range, but this should reduce the occurrences. The default ports
are 35357 and 35358.

Change-Id: I8cfb53d8f90c1ff1fb1083c59fefabca3d14323b
Partial-Bug: #1253482
(cherry picked from commit 6cae83efd72133adae891da0665f51f526705592)

commit_message:
Add requirement for APIImpact flag

Adds a requirement for an APIImpact flag in
the commit message for a proposed spec if it proposes
changes to the Designate REST API. This will make it
much easier for people such as the API WG who want to
review API changes across OpenStack to find and
review proposed API changes.

Change-Id: I4ce6a27127cd0af21d4a160ce446076c38258874

commit_message:
Enabled check for non-critical issues in pylint

Note, R0801 (code duplication check) need to be disabled in current and
previous commits for this change. Parser expects that each problem report
is one-linear.

Change-Id: I3dcd5cd6042972d5e4d5c1decb7fcdfe0b7f3a35
Closes-Bug: #1367971

commit_message:
Disabled code duplication check in pylint

Code duplication report
1. useless since we have a lot of similar plugins and it is hard to
   avoid code duplication
2. breaks lintstack work since report uses more than 1 line

Change-Id: I42e35a5a23eceb2c670ceaa2275c289e08056a9b
Related-Bug: #1367971

commit_message:
Split out compute filters unit tests

It's a terribly-named filter, the ComputeFilter, since it does nothing
other than inspect the service disabled field and the servicegroup API.
Regardless, we move these unit tests out into their own file.

Change-Id: I8655634f947c68b0a26eae40f8357137138a900a

commit_message:
Remove unnecessary try/except in container delete

It appears that the keystone sessions no longer trap the server error
responses in an undesirable way, so this is not necessary anymore.

commit_message:
Update Order models

This CR updates the Order models to use the revamped Orders API.  There
are two concrete Order classes: KeyOrder and AsymmetricOrder which can
be used to create typed orders with types 'key' and 'asymmetric'
respectively.

Change-Id: I0bfb221d1ee00ae3e26be77afc32c7da9cbc59ca

(4 comments)

Susanne--  While I appreciate having easy to use tools for generating diagrams and documentation, part of the idea here is to add stuff that the automatic documentation-generation tools (sphinx in this case) can readily turn into diagrams. For sequence diagrams, other projects are using the 'seqdiag' plugin to sphinx as described here:  http://blockdiag.com/en/seqdiag/sphinxcontrib.html

Also, there's a small sample of the same in specs/template.rst

Could you please update this review to use the seqdiag methods which will be automatically turned into documentation by the tools already in this project?"}, {'account_id': 6951, 'date': '2014-10-23 07:01:04.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2:

Susanne --I've got a decent sphinx seqdiag going. It's actually pretty good.

https://review.openstack.org/#/c/130424/2

You have to build it with tox first then it will generate the html file in the octavia/doc/build/html/design/version0.5 directory."}, {'account_id': 6437, 'date': '2014-10-30 13:57:52.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2:

commit_message:
Make resource tracker always use Flavor objects

Make sure that even when the Flavor is extracted from the instance by
_get_instance_type, it is always a Flavor object we can work with.

Also fix test_tracker.py tests to actually extract the flavor from the
instance, and not fall back on Flavor.get_by_id in
ResourceTracker,_get_instance_type, since we should really never hit
that under normal circumstances.

Change-Id: If704ac386bd4f35dbb7b8e5c46fdd240445ee0a4
Blueprint: virt-driver-cpu-pinning

commit_message:
Update python-saharaclient to 0.7.5 version

A new version of saharaclient allows use cinder volume types and
availability zones. Update of client need for integration these
features in Heat and Horizon.

Change-Id: I6fe951d022bcfcb45a67886c33aec026d2310666

commit_message:
Check fixed-cidr is within fixed-range-v4

Creating a network using 'nova network-create' allows the
creation of fixed IPs that fall outside the fixed-range-v4,
resulting in invalid fixed IPs. The following patch add a
check to see if the fixed-cidr subnet is within the
fixed-range-v4 and throws an exception if it does not.

Change-Id: I00458b54094d3371da63d22e3356660194e2fb95
Closes-Bug: #1367060

commit_message:
Bump testtools version to support message parameter in assertIn

Commit aa67a51299faa5e51da2e96fcf3b0ba3fc2ddc86 introduced usage of the
`message` parameter to `assertIn`.

The current minimium version of `testtools` doesn't support it, so we need to
bump up to at least version 0.3.6.

Change-Id: I8cc95b0f7fbd6439b718dcd5184bb5c34cbddaff
Closes-Bug: 1387870

commit_message:
Fix NetApp AutoSupport Shortcomings.

This patch addresses several problems with the current implementation.

1. Appending a record to EMS should not in itself trigger ASUP
delivery. These should be separately scheduled and Openstack cinder
should have no role in ASUP scheduling or delivery, only a role in
logging via EMS.

2. Log frequency should be adjusted from weekly to hourly.

3. The log message should be useful for support. It should include
release (Havana, Icehouse, Juno, etc.) version (2014.1.1), and
distribution information (RHEL-OSP, etc.) rather than simply noting that
the message came from "Openstack."

Closes-Bug: 1367676
Change-Id: I2f81fed18342fe384e3c61184948f1e4052765d5

commit_message:
Fixed API bug for datasource tables queried through policy

Previously, the API would always report empty tables for
any datasource table queried through policy.  For example,
asking for all rows of the 'neutron:ports' table occurring in
the policy 'classification' would always return the empty set.

This change fixes the behavior to ensure the proper rows
are returned.  There was a typo in the get_arity function
inside the policy engine runtime: using the fully qualified
name 'neutron:ports' instead of just the table name 'ports'.

Closes-bug: 1387879

[{'account_id': 11155, 'date': '2014-10-28 22:19:25.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 1.'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2014-10-28 22:22:32.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Verified-1

- gate-monasca-ui-pep8 http://logs.openstack.org/89/131589/1/check/gate-monasca-ui-pep8/2f380b1 : SUCCESS in 1m 34s
- gate-monasca-ui-python27 http://logs.openstack.org/89/131589/1/check/gate-monasca-ui-python27/a214e7d : FAILURE in 1m 37s'}, {'account_id': 6650, 'date': '2014-10-29 01:13:00.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1: Code-Review-1

(1 comment)

missed import statement.  the reason this wasn't caught before is that this file was in an ignored folder"}, {'account_id': 11155, 'date': '2014-10-29 14:35:24.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 2.'}, {'account_id': 6230, 'date': '2014-10-29 14:38:35.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

I am trying to understand the motivation for this change beyond better egg packaging. The code in and below the monitoring module is the monasca-ui while the files in enabled/ and local_settings.py are meant as sample configuration files that need to be copied (in the case of enabled) into horizon folders or appended (in the case of local_settings.py) into horizon/openstack_dashboard/local/local_settings.py. 

That is why the config files are consciously segregated from the monitoring code and we use egg to copy them into a different location. Are you proposing a different model for integrating extensions into horizon?'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2014-10-29 14:44:29.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2: Verified+1

Build succeeded (check pipeline).

- gate-monasca-ui-pep8 http://logs.openstack.org/89/131589/2/check/gate-monasca-ui-pep8/3f827a4 : SUCCESS in 1m 43s
- gate-monasca-ui-python27 http://logs.openstack.org/89/131589/2/check/gate-monasca-ui-python27/a86ca9d : SUCCESS in 2m 35s'}, {'account_id': 6650, 'date': '2014-10-29 16:19:22.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2:

Rob - With this change, you can install it via an egg (or by a deb installing an egg), then you only need to make config changes on horizon to get it to work.

Making it so you require extra copy steps of these files is not really needed with this approach.   This simplifies our usage of manasca and horizon.'}, {'account_id': 6230, 'date': '2014-10-29 16:49:45.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2:

Hey Eric and Ryan

The question then is how do we get the enabled files onto the system so they can be added to horizon?

I would argue that adding those files into the software base is a bit of a hack. The configuration files just happen to be written in python.  Once they are in the PYTHON PATH they could get loaded from where they are deployed rather then should only get loaded from horizons path.

Tuskar UI originally drove the extension mechanism into horizon. They have the enabled files in the root outside are dont seem to be delivered in the egg.
https://github.com/openstack/tuskar-ui

Looking at how you (Eric) added socorro add your old job, you delivered the egg and the enabled files separately in the same commit.

So it seems like a lot of people have this issue but no one has the solution other than delivering out of band and documenting this.

Is there another way? Perhaps by changing Horizons extension mechanism? Ideally, you would only need to add dependency to Horizons requirements.txt and then horizon would discover and invoke configuration based on searching the namespace.'}, {'account_id': 11155, 'date': '2014-10-29 17:08:49.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2:

Enabling those files is just a couple line change to the settings.py file:

+import monitoring.enabled
+
INSTALLED_APPS = list(INSTALLED_APPS)  # Make sure it's mutable
settings.update_dashboards([
    openstack_dashboard.enabled,
    openstack_dashboard.local.enabled,
+    monitoring.enabled,
], HORIZON_CONFIG, INSTALLED_APPS)"}, {'account_id': 6230, 'date': '2014-10-29 19:16:36.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2:

If I understand you correctly, you are proposing editing horizon's settings.py to let horizon know about the dashboard. That is how one used to install horizon dashboards before the extension mechanism was introduced.  Why not skip the enabled file completely and go back to adding your dashboard into INSTALLED_APPS directly?

I believe the extension mechanism was introduced to have to a drop in model similar to how eclipse has plugins added by dropping in files in a directory rather than editing files."}, {'account_id': 6650, 'date': '2014-10-29 20:38:56.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2:

you could do both if you like (drop them into the standard install location and keep them in the python path), but right now the data_files specified in setup.cfg doesn't even drop them into a standard folder - right?"}, {'account_id': 6230, 'date': '2014-10-30 00:54:44.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2: Code-Review-1

OK. I see how this meets your needs better and how others can make it work.
-1'ed just to ask you to update README.md as well. At least for the new locations of enabled and local_settings.

I also realize the git URLs in README are outdated. I can change that if you don't.

Monasca-vagrant will need to change as well. Again, I can change if you are not using this.

Thanks"}, {'account_id': 11155, 'date': '2014-10-30 21:04:23.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 3.'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2014-10-30 21:08:26.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3: Verified+1

Build succeeded (check pipeline).

commit_message:
Fix vanilla test_get_configs() for i386

When tests are executed on i386, default config values such as
10737418240 are instances of long, whereas when tests are executed
on amd64, the same value is an instance of int.

Closes-bug: 1386743
Change-Id: Iceeb557f3daf40ab4a2ca0dec886e1a646f3b6ef

commit_message:
Forbid replica provisioning from non-root replica site

Reasons:
- Replication V1 should allow only flat hierarchy - one root replica
  with multiple read replicas. Trove should forbid attempts to create
  slave of slave of slave and so on.

Changes:
- adding validation step that forbids read replica provisioning if passed
  root replica (slave_if_id) is not an actual root (is a read replica any
  other root replica).

Change-Id: I45eb8f13ea170358da1de2ab546c9e0c75034963
Closes-Bug: #1357707

commit_message:
Return 403 on unauthorized upload when over account quota

If you try an unauthorized upload into a container that is over quota you get
a 403 instead of a 413, but if you try to unauthorized upload when an
*account* is over quota you can see the 413 even though the upload would have
been rejected by the authorize callback.  By wrapping the authorize callback
associated with the incoming request we can make sure to only return our 413
when the request would have been authorized otherwise.

Drive by doc fixes thanks to acoles:

 * State that container_quotas should be after auth middleware in
   the class doc string.
 * Add note to proxy-server.conf.sample that account_quotas should
   be after auth middleware.

The equivalent statements are already in place for each quota
middleware.

Doc-Impact

Change-Id: I2a88b3ec79d35bfdd73ea6ad64e376b7c7af4ea6
Closes-Bug: #1387415

Change-Id: I64eb70d7668c2c5e106f1c7b64ce49924325f5e9

commit_message:
Fix wrong arg number for _fix_id_migration issue

If the provider_location doesn't contain the name of the volume, TGT and
ISER will fail on doing a id migration, due to wrong number of
arguments.

Change-Id: I420ceaf14edfb6a0e3b8fd1f50070dc70b6f16bd
Closes-Bug: #1386902

[{'created': '2014-10-23 14:52:42.000000000', 'message': 'VMware: Improve the efficiency of vm_util.get_host_name_for_vm

get_host_name_for_vm was extremely and unnecessarily inefficient. In
fetching a host, it:

1. Got the host_ref for the VM
2. Threw away the type component of the host_ref
3. Retrieved all HostSystem objects known to vSphere
4. Searched them for the object matching the value component of the
   host_ref
5. Retrieved the name property from the returned component

The new implementation does:

1. Get the host_ref for the VM
2. Get the name property of the HostSystem object with that host_ref

Consequently, the following functions are no longer used, and go away:

* get_host_ref_from_id
* property_from_property_set
* get_host_id_from_vm_ref

get_host_ref_for_vm is modified in both its implementation (see
above), and to return the host_ref its name suggests rather than an
ObjectContent object.

Change-Id: I89a731b2c5df61f031b93c861b2e4a222da49e99
'}]
commit_message:
VMware: Improve the efficiency of vm_util.get_host_name_for_vm

get_host_name_for_vm was extremely and unnecessarily inefficient. In
fetching a host, it:

1. Got the host_ref for the VM
2. Threw away the type component of the host_ref
3. Retrieved all HostSystem objects known to vSphere
4. Searched them for the object matching the value component of the
   host_ref
5. Retrieved the name property from the returned component

The new implementation does:

1. Get the host_ref for the VM
2. Get the name property of the HostSystem object with that host_ref

Consequently, the following functions are no longer used, and go away:

* get_host_ref_from_id
* property_from_property_set
* get_host_id_from_vm_ref

get_host_ref_for_vm is modified in both its implementation (see
above), and to return the host_ref its name suggests rather than an
ObjectContent object.

commit_message:
VMware: Improve logging on failure due to invalid guestId

If a glance image has a vmware_ostype property which doesn't
correspond to a valid VMware guestId, VM creation will fail with the
unhelpfully generic error message:

A specified parameter was not correct.

This change improves this situation slightly by logging a warning if
VM creation fails and guestId is not a recognised value. We limit
ourselves to logging a warning because we don't want to tightly couple
ourselves to the vSphere behaviour. We can't guarantee that this is
the reason the RPC call failed, or that it is the only reason the RPC
call failed.

DocImpact

This change doesn't impact the behaviour of the VMware driver except
that it will emit an additional warning message to the logs under the
circumstances described. However, given the potential for
user misconfiguration, we should describe this pitfall in the docs.

Closes-Bug: #1357263

here's a patch that implements my recommendation for test_imagebackend.py (as i'm not quite comfortable uploading a new patchset without having conferred with you): http://paste.openstack.org/show/126312/"}, {'account_id': 11069, 'date': '2014-10-29 08:57:48.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3:

(8 comments)

i'm not sure disable_process_locking needs to be handled at all in test_vm_utils.py as the tests in question don't appear to exercise any code paths that dereference "disable_process_locking".  another convincing argument is that the tests passed with patch set 3 (when disable_process_locking wasn't really set) and after i patched it.  but if we insist on migrating the original file, as-is, then here's a patch for test_vm_utils.py: http://paste.openstack.org/show/126348/

here's a patch for test_xenapi.py: http://paste.openstack.org/show/126365/.  the patch might not change the test results (ie whether disable_process_locking is really set True or not), but it changes the code paths tested because if lock_path is not set (eg you run the tests directly with ".venv/bin/python -m testtools.run nova.tests.virt.xenapi.test_xenapi") then you get 59 "lock_path not set" failures with patch set 3, but only 10 failures after my changes (which makes sense because when disable_process_locking is true, as in my patch, then we don't use external locks that require a lock path, but instead internal locks that don't require a file system path).

WARNING: because set_override is not automatically undone at the end of tests, then we technically need to insure the corresponding clear_override is called by adding it to cleanup (ie addCleanup()).  i was lazy in my patches and used tearDown(), but that's not called if setUp failed, except i did use addCleanup when set_override was called within a test where there's no corresponding tearDown to add the clear_override to.'}, {'account_id': 5638, 'date': '2014-10-29 11:28:15.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 4.'}, {'account_id': 5638, 'date': '2014-10-29 11:30:58.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 4:

commit_message:
Switch Nova to use oslo.concurrency

Let's switch to the newly released oslo library for the
processutils and lockutils. We use the config fixture(s) to
specify disable_process_locking and lock_path in the CONF
variable of oslo.concurrency library for correctly setting the
flags.

The previous attempt at updating nova to use oslo.concurrency
was reverted as it stopped running any tests. lockutils-wrapper
should have been used in ini/shell scripts
instead of lockutils.py module as the the module is
no longer runnable (__main__ has been removed).  In this
review we use lockutils-wrapper correctly. The test harness
has since been updated to bail out if 0 tests are run as
well for additional insurance.

Change-Id: I14c75ef2196fd08c9465d648e5cd53777bd9c7d1
Co-Authored-By: Nikola Dipanov <ndipanov@redhat.com>

Adds tests for Hyper-V Network utils

Adds unit tests for Hyper-V NetworkUtils and NetworkUtilsV2 classes.

Partial-Bug: #1220256

commit_message:
Bump version string

After the first tempest lib release the version string was never
incremented. This commit corrects the issue.

Change-Id: Iaf2ef6631f6a919e12ee504caecf7222e371eec3

commit_message:
Add debug output indicating provider_location

Just add a simple debug statement to indicate the resultant
provider location of a tgtadm volume after create_export.

Change-Id: Ide12986400c54978ee5b387d615b203c0f93f029

commit_message:
Improve share-network list API filtering

Add filtering share-network list by creation date, associated security
service ID, project ID (for admin context only).

Limit share network list using 'offset' and 'limit' options.

Add policy rule for 'get_all_share_networks' action.

Remove 'status' field from returned share nerwork's view,
as share_network model doesn't have such attribute. So, None was always
returned as a status.

Fix DB api function share_network_get_all_by_security_service - second param
should be named 'security_service_id' instead of 'share_network_id'.

Add unit and tempest tests.

Implements bp improve-share-network-list-filtering

Change-Id: I7c3e44068fb39672d1d6c9e06527fde2604672a9

Use proper value for osap_share_extension

Fixes the following warning when running tempest:

  osapi_share_extension is set to deprecated path:
    manila.api.openstack.share.contrib.standard_extensions
  Please set your flag or manila.conf settings for osapi_share_extension to:
    manila.api.contrib.standard_extensions

you'll need to modify tempest tests to get this to pass... that said, this might be better as a middleware filter so the default behaviour isn't changed. while i'm more incline to agree and says it's better to restrict completely to admin only, i think based on bug discussion this would be too restrictive to others."}, {'account_id': 6873, 'date': '2014-10-27 14:38:07.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2:

@gordc, Yeah I guess this does impose an upgrade impact since if you were getting meter information from a non-admin before it's going to blow up with this change.

I don't really know how the middleware change would work here, can you elaborate?  Do you mean changing something in the api-paste.ini?

https://github.com/openstack/ceilometer/blob/master/etc/ceilometer/api_paste.ini

Or something in oslo.middleware with CADF?"}, {'account_id': 6676, 'date': '2014-10-28 12:35:04.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2: Code-Review-1

the meter list is documented in our document, and I think https://github.com/openstack/ceilometer/blob/master/ceilometer/api/controllers/v2.py#L358 _sanitize_query will limit the normal user'}, {'account_id': 10608, 'date': '2014-10-28 14:13:17.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2: Code-Review-1

Security should trump backwards compatibility.

The implementation of _sanitize_query() seems to represent a misunderstanding of OpenStack RBAC...

A user with the admin role has that role for a specific project. They should not have access to the data in other projects unless they are also admins of those other projects.

And a non-admin user should not necessarily be able to see all data for their project... E.g. they should only be able to view http.request/response meter data associated with their own userid (allowing access to all non-admin users within the project is what led to the opening of this defect, since non-admin user bob should not be able to see what another user joe is doing, or even that that user exists). It would be appropriate for a non-admin user to access the data for some other meters across the project, so the decision to allow or reject access would need to be meter-specific.

As a workaround until we can get those blueprints implemented, I think we need to a) restrict admin access to the project to which the token is scoped and b) further restrict http.request and http.response meter access to admins.'}, {'account_id': 6537, 'date': '2014-10-28 18:14:27.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2:

@mriedem i don't really have a fully fleshed out idea but i would think, if you created a middleware that exists after keystonemiddleware.auth_token, you may be able to analyse the role there and block request at that point?

i'm not sure how much work that would be... that might end up covering a lot of the RBAC bp scope."}, {'account_id': 10987, 'date': '2014-10-29 08:58:05.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2: Code-Review-1

(1 comment)

One question is inline.

Cheers, Igor.'}, {'account_id': 6484, 'date': '2014-10-30 00:42:27.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2: Code-Review-1

Why not using a configuration? We were running into the similar issue for our billing system. Our initial design is making every endpoint as admin only. Then we found it will cause some problems when user want to see the billing data from Horizon.'}, {'account_id': 10608, 'date': '2014-10-30 19:30:10.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2:

I've submitted an alternative change for review. See https://review.openstack.org/#/c/132097/"}, {'account_id': 6873, 'date': '2014-10-30 19:34:10.000000000', 'content': "Abandoned

Going to abandon for Matthew's more targeted fix:

https://review.openstack.org/#/c/132097/"}]

commit_message:
Block non-admin user to get meters

Currently, all users can get meters in Ceilometer. This is a
security issue. Ceilometer never supported any kind of policy
so far. The only one supported is used to determine if a user
is an admin or not. This patch blocks non-admin users to get
meters.

This is a workaround until blueprint advanced-policy-rule
and/or blueprint admin-only-api-access are implemented.

Change-Id: Ib70ec4e3ba967fa63e8aba99c8ecb463fc085fa2
Related-Bug: #1376915
Co-authored-by: Zhi Kun Liu <zhikunli@cn.ibm.com>

commit_message:
Deletes floating ip related connection states

When a floating ip is dissociated with a port, the current
connection with the floating ip is still working. This patch
will clear the connection state and cut off the connection
immediately.

Since conntrack -D will return 1, which is not an error code,
so add extra_ok_codes argument to execute methods.

Change-Id: Ia9bd7ae243a0859dcb97e2fa939f7d16f9c2456c
Closes-Bug: 1334926

commit_message:
Enhance rally info

* Add "rally info BenchmarkScenario", "rally info DeployEgnine" etc.
* Simplify the default "rally info" output
* Add SLA support
